\n|Laci Collins\n|TV film\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n|Mrs. Diana Annenburg\n|\"The Doctor in the Den\"\n|-\n|2009\u20132011\n|''{{sortname|The|Office|The Office (U.S. TV series)}}''\n|[[List of The Office (U.S. TV series) characters#Helene Beesly|Helene Beesly]]\n|Recurring role (seasons 6\u20137)\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Desperate Housewives]]''\n|Lillian Allen\n|\"A Little Night Music\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Criminal Minds]]''\n|Colleen Everson\n|\"Our Darkest Hour\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Lie to Me]]''\n|Meredith Spencer\n|\"In the Red\"\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]''\n|Elizabeth Gaines\n|\"Semper I\", \"Achilles Heel\", \"Marine One\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[True Blood]]''\n|Barbara Pelt\n|\"Whatever I Am, You Made Me\", \"We'll Meet Again\"\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Stalked at 17]]''\n|Lauren\n|TV film\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Major Crimes (TV series)|Major Crimes]]''\n|Doris\n|\"Flight Risk\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Reckless (TV series)|Reckless]]''\n|Barbara Fortnum\n|\"Blind Sides\", \"Deep Waters\", \"51%\", \"And So It Begins\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Designated Survivor (TV series)|Designated Survivor]]''\n|Julia Rombauer\n|\"The Ninth Seat\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''{{sortname|The|Oath|The Oath (U.S. TV series)}}''\n|Gwenn Hammond\n|Recurring role\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Code Black (TV series)|Code Black]]''\n|Madeline Mandel\n|\"Change of Heart\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Matlock characters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.lindapurl.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|0700909}}\n* [http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=14153 Linda Purl] (Aveleyman)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purl, Linda}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Finch College alumni]]\n[[Category:American School in Japan alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Eric Pode lives", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision:spaced en-dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linda_Purl"}
{"title_page": "Curleywee", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Curleywee\n| photo = Curleywee1.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 674\n| elevation_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref>\n| prominence_m = 119\n| prominence_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref>\n| listing = [[Donald (hill)|Donald]]\n| location = [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = Minnigaff Hills, [[Galloway Hills]], [[Southern Uplands]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NX 45471 76952\n| map = \n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 77\n}}\n\n'''Curleywee''' is a hill in the Minnigaff Hills range in the [[Galloway Hills]], part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. It is normally ascended with [[Lamachan Hill]] as part of a round normally starting from the north or south.<ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref> The name of the hill is said to derive from Scottish Gaelic ''Cor Le Gaoith'' (hill in the wind).<ref>https://www.screel.co.uk/walks/dumfries-galloway/curleywee/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Curleywee\n| photo = Curleywee1.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 674\n| elevation_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref>\n| prominence_m = 119\n| prominence_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref>\n| listing = [[Donald (hill)|Donald]]\n| location = [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = Minnigaff Hills, [[Galloway Hills]], [[Southern Uplands]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NX 45471 76952\n| map = \n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 77\n}}\n\n'''Curleywee''' is a hill in the Minnigaff Hills range in the [[Galloway Hills]], part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. It is normally ascended with [[Lamachan Hill]] as part of a round normally starting from the north or south. <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?rf=1704</ref> The name of the hill is said to derive from Scottish Gaelic ''Cor Le Gaoith'' (hill in the wind). <ref>https://www.screel.co.uk/walks/dumfries-galloway/curleywee/</ref>\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curleywee"}
{"title_page": "Craniofacial cleft", "text_new": "A '''facial cleft''' is an opening or gap in the [[face]], or a malformation of a part of the face. Facial clefts is a collective term for all sorts of clefts. All structures like bone, soft tissue, skin etc. can be affected. Facial clefts are extremely rare [[congenital anomalies]]. There are many variations of a type of clefting and classifications are needed to describe and classify all types of clefting. Facial clefts hardly ever occur isolated; most of the time there is an overlap of adjacent facial clefts.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=10332258 |year=1996 |last1=Moore |first1=MH |title=Rare craniofacial clefts |volume=7 |issue=6 |pages=408\u201311 |journal=The Journal of Craniofacial Surgery |doi=10.1097/00001665-199611000-00003}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n== Classifications ==\nThere are different classifications about facial clefts. Two of the most used classifications are the '''Tessier classification'''<ref>{{ cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0301-0503(76)80013-6 |pmid=820824 |title=Anatomical classification of facial, cranio-facial and latero-facial clefts |year=1976 |last1=Tessier |first1=P |journal=Journal of Maxillofacial Surgery |volume=4 |pages=69\u201392 |issue=2}}</ref> and the '''Van der Meulen classification'''.<ref name = \"Van der Meulen\">{{cite journal | author = Van der Meulen, JCH | title = Facial Clefts | journal = World J. Surg. | volume = 13 | pages = 373\u2013383 | year = 1989 |doi=10.1007/BF01660750| pmid =2773497 | issue = 4 | displayauthors = etal  }}</ref> Tessier is based on the anatomical position of the cleft and Van der Meulen classification is based on the embryogenesis.\n\n=== Tessier classification ===\n[[File:Picture Tessier classification.jpg|thumb|right|Tessier classification. Left: boney clefts, Right: Soft tissue clefts.]]\nIn 1976 [[Paul Tessier]] published a classification on facial clefts based on the anatomical position of the clefts. The different types of Tessier clefts are numbered 0 to 14. These 15 different types of clefts can be put into 4 groups, based on their position:<ref>Fearon, JA et al. \"Rare Craniofacial Clefts: A surgical Classification\", J Craniofac Surg. 2008 Jan;19(1):110-2,{{ cite journal |doi=10.1097/SCS.0b013e31815ca1ba| pmid=18216674 |year=2008 |last1=Fearon |first1=JA |title=Rare craniofacial clefts: a surgical classification |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=110\u20132 |journal=The Journal of Craniofacial Surgery }}</ref> midline clefts, paramedian clefts, orbital clefts and lateral clefts. The Tessier classification describes the clefts at soft tissue level as well as at bone level, because it appears that the soft tissue clefts can have a slightly different location on the face than the bony clefts.\n\n==== Midline clefts ====\nThe midline clefts are Tessier number 0 (\"median craniofacial dysplasia\"), number 14 ([[frontonasal dysplasia]]), and number 30 (\"lower midline facial cleft\", also known as \"median mandibular cleft\"). These clefts bisect the face vertically through the midline. Tessier number 0 bisects the [[maxilla]] and the nose, Tessier number 14 comes between the nose and the [[frontal bone]]. The Tessier number 30 facial cleft is through the tongue, lower lip and [[mandible]]. The tongue may be absent, hypoplastic, bifid, or even duplicated.<ref name=Bhattacharyya2012>{{cite journal|last=Bhattacharyya|first=NC|last2=Kalita|first2=K|last3=Gogoi|first3=M|last4=Deuri|first4=PK|title=Tessier 30 facial cleft|journal=Journal of Indian Association of Pediatric Surgeons|volume=17|issue=2|pages=75\u20137|year=2012|doi=10.4103/0971-9261.93970|pmc=3326828|pmid=22529554}}</ref> People with this condition may be [[Ankyloglossia|tongue-tied]].<ref name=Bhattacharyya2012/>\n\n==== Paramedian clefts ====\nTessier number 1, 2, 12 and 13 are the paramedian clefts. These clefts are quite similar to the midline clefts, but they are further away from the midline of the face. Tessier number 1 and 2 both come through the maxilla and the nose, in which Tessier number 2 is further from the midline ([[Lateral (anatomy)|lateral]]) than number 1. Tessier number 12 is in extent of number 2, positioned between nose and frontal bone, while Tessier number 13 is in extent of number 1, also running between nose and forehead. Both 12 and 13 run between the midline and the orbit.\n\n==== Orbital clefts ====\nTessier number 3, 4, 5, 9, 10 and 11 are orbital clefts. These clefts all have the involvement of the [[Orbit (anatomy)|orbit]]. Tessier number 3, 4, and 5 are positioned through the maxilla and the orbital floor. Tessier number 9, 10 and 11 are positioned between the upper side of the orbit and the forehead or between the upper side of the orbit and the [[temple]] of the head. \nLike the other clefts, Tessier number 11 is in extent to number 3, number 10 is in extent to number 4 and number 9 is in extent to number 5.\n\n==== Lateral clefts ====\nThe lateral clefts are the clefts which are positioned horizontally on the face. These are Tessier number 6, 7 and 8. Tessier number 6 runs from the orbit to the cheek bone. Tessier number 7 is positioned on the line between the corner of the mouth and the ear. A possible lateral cleft comes from the corner of the mouth towards the ear, which gives the impression that the mouth is bigger. It\u2019s also possible that the cleft begins at the ear and runs towards the mouth. Tessier number 8 runs from the outer corner of the eye towards the ear. \nThe combination of a Tessier number 6-7-8 is seen in the [[Treacher Collins syndrome]]. Tessier number 7 is more related to [[hemifacial microsomia]] and number 8 is more related to [[Goldenhar syndrome]].\n\n=== Van der Meulen classification ===\nVan der Meulen classification divides different types of clefts based on where the development arrest occurs in the [[embryogenesis]]. A primary cleft can occur in an early stage of the development of the face (17&nbsp;mm length of the embryo). The developments arrests can be divided in four different location groups: internasal, [[human nose|nasal]], nasalmaxillar and maxillar. The maxillar location can be subdivided in [[median]] and lateral clefts.\n \n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile: Van_der_meulen_-_internasal_dysplasia.jpg | Internasal dysplasia\nFile: Nasal_dysplasia.jpg | Nasal dysplasia\nFile: Nasalmaxillary_dysplasia.jpg | Nasomaxillary dysplasia\nFile: Maxillary_dysplasia.jpg | Maxillary dysplasia\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==== Internasal dysplasia ====\nInternasal [[dysplasia]] is caused by a development arrest before the union of the both nasal halves. These clefts are characterized by a median cleft lip, a median notch of the [[cupid's bow]] or a duplication of the labial [[frenulum]]. Besides the median cleft lip, [[hypertelorism]] can be seen in these clefts. Also sometimes there can be an underdevelopment of the [[premaxilla]].\n\n==== Nasal dysplasia ====\nNasal dysplasia or nasoschisis is caused by a development arrest of the lateral side of the nose, resulting in a cleft in one of the nasal halves. The nasal septum and cavity can be involved, though this is rare. Nasoschisis is also characterized by hypertelorism.\n\n==== Nasomaxillary dysplasia ====\nNasomaxillary dysplasia is caused by a development arrest at the junction of the lateral side of the nose and the maxilla, which results in a complete or non-complete cleft between the nose and the orbital floor (nasoocular cleft) or between the mouth, nose and the orbital floor (oronasal-ocular cleft). The development of the lip is normal.\n\n==== Maxillary dysplasia ====\nMaxillary dysplasia can manifest itself on two different locations in the maxilla: in the medial or the lateral part of the maxilla.\n* '''''Median maxillary dysplasia''''' is caused by a development failure of the medial part of the maxillary [[ossification center]]s. This results in secondary clefting of the lip, [[philtrum]] and palate. Clefting from the maxilla to the orbital floor has also been reported.\n* '''''Lateral maxillary dysplasia''''' is caused by a development failure of the lateral part of the maxillary ossification centers, which also results in secondary clefting of the lip and palate. Clefting of the lateral part of the lower eyelid is typical for lateral maxillary dysplasia.\n==Causes==\nIt is possible that facial clefts are caused by a disorder in the migration of [[neural crest cell]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/01.PRS.0000070971.95846.9C |pmid =12900623 |title=Common Craniofacial Anomalies: Facial Clefts and Encephaloceles |year=2003 |last1=Hunt |first1=Jeremy A. |last2=Hobar |first2=P. Craig |journal=Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery |volume=112 |issue=2 |pages=606\u2013616}}</ref>\n\nAnother theory is that facial clefts are caused by failure of the fusion process and failure of inwards growth of the [[mesoderm]].\n\nOther theories are that genetics play a part in the development of facial clefts<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3109/02844316709006555 |title=Genetic and Non-Genetic Factors in the Etiology of Facial Clefts |year=1967 |last1=Fogh-Andersen |first1=P. |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery and Hand Surgery |volume=1 |pages=22\u201329}}</ref> or that they are caused by amniotic bands.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=6794056 |year=1981 |last1=Mayou |first1=BJ |last2=Fenton |first2=OM |title=Oblique facial clefts caused by amniotic bands |volume=68 |issue=5 |pages=675\u201381 |journal=Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery |doi=10.1097/00006534-198111000-00001}}</ref>\n\n=== Genetics ===\n\n==== Overview ====\nAround one in 700 individuals are born with craniofacial clefts<ref name=\":1\">Leslie, E.J., and Marazita, M.L. (2013). Genetics of Cleft Lip and Cleft Palate. Am J Med Genet C Semin Med Genet 163, 246\u2013258.</ref>. There are multiple genetic and environmental factors which contribute to craniofacial development. Within craniofacial disorders and [[Craniofacial abnormality|abnormalities]], orofacial clefts, and specifically [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|cleft lip]] (CL) and [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|cleft palate]] (CP) are the most common in humans<ref name=\":1\" />. Occurrences of CL/P are most often (around seventy percent of cases) isolated and nonsyndromic, meaning they are not associated with a syndrome or inherited genetic conditions<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Yoon, A.J., Pham, B.N., and Dipple, K.M. (2016). Genetic Screening in Patients with Craniofacial Malformations. J Pediatr Genet 5, 220\u2013224.</ref>. Around thirty percent occur with other structural variances, and over 500 syndromes have been identified in which clefting is a principal feature<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Clefting can result from [[Teratology|teratogens]], an agent that disrupts embryo development such as, radiation, maternal infection, chemicals, or drugs<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. [[Chromosome abnormality|Chromosomal abnormalities]] or [[Mutation|mutations]] at single gene loci have also contributed to clefting development<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Genetic causes are linked with most craniofacial syndromes, and CL/P and other orofacial clefts are recognized as [[Heterogeneous condition|heterogeneous disorders]], meaning there are multiple recognized causes<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">Cohen, M.M. (2002). Malformations of the craniofacial region: evolutionary, embryonic, genetic, and clinical perspectives. Am. J. Med. Genet. 115, 245\u2013268.</ref>. Orofacial clefts have great phenotypic diversity, and their associated genetic environments have called for vast research and investigation.\n\n==== Environmental Interaction ====\nCraniofacial disorders have high variance in phenotypic expression, and researchers have suggested this variance could be due to interactions between the mutated/deviated genes and other genes, along with interactions with environmental factors<ref name=\":4\">Weinberg, Seth M., Robert Cornell, and Elizabeth J. Leslie. 2018. \u201cCraniofacial Genetics: Where Have We Been and Where Are We Going?\u201d PLoS Genetics 14 (6): e1007438. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1007438.</ref><ref name=\":5\">Roosenboom, Jasmien, Greet Hens, Brooke C. Mattern, Mark D. Shriver, and Peter Claes. 2016. \u201cExploring the Underlying Genetics of Craniofacial Morphology through Various Sources of Knowledge.\u201d Edited by Ilker ERCAN. BioMed Research International 2016 (December): 3054578. https://doi.org/10.1155/2016/3054578.</ref>. Environmental causes have been found to contribute to craniofacial clefting, however, these are still influenced by and supported by genetic factors. Many studies, for example, have linked maternal smoking to increased CLP risk; however, the increased risk suggests that genes in metabolic pathways could still contribute to susceptibility or formation of CL/P<ref name=\":6\">Dixon, M.J., Marazita, M.L., Beaty, T.H., and Murray, J.C. (2011). Cleft lip and palate: synthesizing genetic and environmental influences. Nat Rev Genet 12, 167\u2013178.</ref>.\n\n==== Development and Inheritance ====\nThe craniofacial complex begins its progress in the fourth week of development, and results from [[neural crest]] cells migrating to form and fuse the facial primordia<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Failures or deviations in this process result in craniofacial clefts, either CL or CP<ref name=\":0\" />. The range of variation in phenotype aligns with ancestry<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" />. Studies have found increased amounts of clefting in the relatives of patients with clefts, suggesting genetic factors are the underlying cause for CL/P<ref name=\":1\" />. Inheritance has a known and significant role in human craniofacial morphology. This is supported through cephalometric and anthropometric comparisons of family members including between triplets, twins, siblings, and parents and children<ref>The Role of Genetics in Craniofacial Morphology and Growth | Annual Review of Anthropology.</ref>.\n\n==== Genetic Experimentation ====\nGenetic factors of craniofacial clefting can be investigated and tracked through several methods including [[sequencing]] in humans, [[Genome-wide association study|Genome-wide association studies]] (GWAs), [[fate mapping]], expression analysis, and animal studies (knockout experiments or models with clefting from chemical mutagenesis)<ref>Facebase.org</ref>. [[Twin study|Twin studies]] and familial clustering have also revealed that facial structure and formation are genetically linked. Several genes have been associated with craniofacial disorders through experimentation, inlcuding sequencing Mendelian clefting syndromes<ref name=\":1\" />. Over 25 loci have been identified as potential influencers of craniofacial clefts across populations<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n==== Linked Genes ====\nThe [[transforming growth factor]] (''TGF'') family has provided multiple candidate genes linked with craniofacial development and malformation<ref name=\":7\">Genetic and Teratogenic Approaches To Craniofacial Development - D.L. Young, R.A. Schneider, D. Hu, J.A. Helms, 2000.</ref><ref name=\":8\">Wilkie, A.O., and Morriss-Kay, G.M. (2001). Genetics of craniofacial development and malformation. Nat. Rev. Genet. 2, 458\u2013468.</ref><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. ''TGF'' is involved in cell migration, differentiation, and proliferation, as well as regulating the extracellular matrix<ref name=\":7\" />. Another gene that has been flagged as causal for craniofacial disorders, including CL/P, is [[IRF6|interferon regulatory factor 6]] or, ''[[IRF6]]''<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\">SPECC1L deficiency results in increased adherens junction stability and reduced cranial neural crest cell delamination. - PubMed - NCBI.</ref>. Mutations in ''IRF6'' cause [[Van der Woude syndrome]], the most common clefting syndrome<ref name=\":1\" />. [[VAX1|Ventral anterior homeobox 1]], ''VAX1,'' and [[Noggin (protein)|noggin]], ''NOG'', were identified with genome-wide significance for contributing to CL/P<ref name=\":6\" />. Additionally, mutations in ''SPECC1L'' have recently been identified as influential to facial structure formation, and as causal for syndromic facial clefting<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Kruszka, P., Li, D., Harr, M.H., Wilson, N.R., Swarr, D., McCormick, E.M., Chiavacci, R.M., Li, M., Martinez, A.F., Hart, R.A., et al. (2015). Mutations in SPECC1L, encoding sperm antigen with calponin homology and coiled-coil domains 1-like, are found in some cases of autosomal dominant Opitz G/BBB syndrome. J. Med. Genet. 52, 104\u2013110.</ref>. Nonsyndromic CL/P has been associated with the transcription factor [[FOXE1|forkhead box protein E1]] (''FOXE1''), as mutations have resulted in cases of CL/P in mice<ref name=\":2\" />. Other genes which have been found to interact with or contribute to craniofacial clefting include ''FGFR''s, ''TWIST'', ''MSX''s, ''GREM1'', ''TCOF1'', ''PAX''s, ''MAFB'', ''ABCA4,'' and ''WNT'' allowing great cause for more research into the genetic basis for craniofacial disorders<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Prevention ==\nBecause the cause of facial clefts still is unclear, it is difficult to say what may prevent children being born with facial clefts. It seems that [[folic acid]] contributes to lowering the risk of a child being born with a facial cleft.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.39079.618287.0B |pmid=17259187 |title=Folic acid supplements and risk of facial clefts: national population based case-control study |year=2007 |last1=Wilcox |first1=A. J |last2=Lie |first2=R. T. |last3=Solvoll |first3=K. |last4=Taylor |first4=J. |last5=McConnaughey |first5=D R. |last6=Abyholm |first6=F. |last7=Vindenes |first7=H. |last8=Vollset |first8=S. E. |last9=Drevon |first9=C. A |journal=BMJ |volume=334 |issue=7591 |pages=464 |pmc=1808175  }}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nThere is no single strategy for treatment of facial clefts, because of the large amount of variation in these clefts. Which kind of surgery is used depends on the type of clefting and which structures are involved. There is much discussion about the timing of reconstruction of bone and soft tissue. The problem with early reconstruction is the recurrence of the deformity due to the intrinsic restricted growth. This requires additional operations at a later age to make sure all parts of the face are in proportion.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.3109/02844318209006569 |pmid= 7051271|title=Adolescent Facial Morphology of Early Bone-Grafted Cleft Lip and Palate Patients|year=1982|last1=Friede|first1=Hans|last2=Johanson|first2=Bengt|journal=Scandinavian Journal of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery and Hand Surgery|volume=16|pages=41\u201353|issue=1}}</ref> A disadvantage of early bone reconstruction is the chance to damage the tooth germs, which are located in the maxilla, just under the orbit. The soft tissue reconstruction can be done at an early age, but only if the used skin flap can be used again during a second operation. The timing of the operation depends on the urgency of the underlying condition. If the operation is necessary to function properly, it should be done at early age. The best aesthetic result is achieved when the incisions are positioned in areas which attract the least attention (they cover up the scars). If, however, the function of a part of the face isn\u2019t damaged, the operation depends on psychological factors and the facial area of reconstruction. \n \nThe treatment plan of a facial cleft is planned right after diagnosis. This plan includes every operation needed in the first 18 years of the patients life to reconstruct the face fully. \nIn this plan, a difference is made between problems that need to be solved to improve the health of the patient (coloboma) and problems that need to be solved for a better cosmetic result (hypertelorism). \n \nThe treatment of the facial clefts can be divided in different areas of the face: the cranial anomalies, the orbital and eye anomalies, the nose anomalies, the midface anomalies and the mouth anomalies.\n\n=== Treatment of the cranial anomalies ===\nThe most common cranial anomaly seen in combination with facial clefts is [[encephalocele]].\n\n==== Encephalocele ====\nThe treatment of encephalocele is based on surgery to repair the bony gap and provide adequate protection of the underlying brain. The question remains if the external brain tissue should be put back into the skull or if it is possible to cut off that piece of brain tissue, because its claimed that the external piece of brain tissue often isn\u2019t functional,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1288/00005537-198208000-00008 |pmid= 7098736 |year=1982 |last1=Kamerer |first1=Donald B. |title= Temporal Bone Encephalocele ??? Diagnosis and Treatment |last2=Caparosa |first2=Ralph J. |journal=The Laryngoscope |volume=92 |issue=8 |pages=878\u2013882}}</ref> with the exception of a basal encephalocele, in which the pituitary gland can be found in the mouth.\n\n=== Treatment of orbital / eye anomalies ===\nThe most common orbital /eye anomalies seen in children with facial clefts are colobomas and vertical dystopia.\n\n==== Coloboma ====\nThe coloboma which occurs often in facial clefts is a cleft in the lower or upper eyelid. This should be closed as soon as possible, to prevent drought of the eye and a consecutive loss of vision.<ref>Patipa M et al., \"Surgical management of congenital eyelid coloboma\", Ophthalmic Surg. 1982 Mar;13(3):212-216 {{cite journal |pmid=7088491 |year=1982 |last1=Patipa |first1=M |last2=Wilkins |first2=RB |last3=Guelzow |first3=KW |title=Surgical management of congenital eyelid coloboma |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=212\u20136 |journal=Ophthalmic Surgery }}</ref>\n\n==== Vertical orbital dystopia ====\nVertical orbital dystopia can occur in facial clefts when the orbital floor and/or the maxilla is involved in the cleft. Vertical orbital dystopia means that the eyes do not lay on the same horizontal line in the face (one eye is positioned lower than the other). The treatment is based on the reconstruction of this orbital floor, by either closing the boney cleft or reconstructing the orbital floor using a [[bone graft]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/SCS.0b013e3181e57241 |pmid=20613583 |title=Orbital Floor Reconstruction |year=2010 |last1=Tabrizi |first1=Reza |last2=Ozkan |first2=Taha Birkan |last3=Mohammadinejad |first3=Cyrus |last4=Minaee |first4=Nasim |journal=Journal of Craniofacial Surgery |volume=21 |issue=4 |pages=1142\u20131146 }}</ref>\n\n==== Hypertelorism ====\nThere are many types of operations which can be performed to treat a hypertelorism. 2 options are: box osteotomy and facial bipartition<ref>Marchad D & Arnaud E, \"Midface surgery from Tessier to distraction\", Childs Nerv Syst. 1999 Nov;15(11-12):681-94, {{ cite journal |doi=10.1007/s003810050458 |pmid= 10603010 |title=Midface surgery from Tessier to distraction |year=1999 |last1=Marchac |first1=D. |last2=Arnaud |first2=Eric |journal=Child's Nervous System |volume=15 |issue=11\u201312 |pages=681\u2013694}}</ref> (also referred to as a median fasciotomy).\nThe goal of the box osteotomy is to bring the orbits closer together by removing a part of the bone between the orbits, to detach both orbits from the surrounding bone structures and move both orbits more to the centre of the face. \nThe goal of the facial bipartition is not only to bring the orbits closer together, but also to create more space in the maxilla. This can be done by splitting the maxilla and the frontal bone, remove a triangular shaped piece of bone from the forehead and nasal bones and pulling the two pieces of forehead together. Not only will the hypertelorism be solved by pulling the frontal bone closer together, but because of this pulling, the space between the both parts of the maxilla will become wider.\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile: Picture_box_osteotomy.jpg|<center> Box Osteotomy </center>\nFile: Picture_median_fasciotomy.jpg | <center> Facial Bipartition </center>\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n=== Treatment of nose anomalies ===\nThe nose anomalies found in facial clefts vary. The main goal of the treatment is to reconstruct the nose to get a functional and esthetic acceptable result. A few possible treatment options are to reconstruct the nose with a forehead flap or reconstruct the nasal dorsum with a bone graft, for example a rib graft. The [[nasal reconstruction]] with a forehead flap is based on the repositioning of a skin flap from the forehead to the nose. A possible downside of this reconstruction is that once you performed it at a younger age, you can\u2019t lengthen the flap at a later stage. A second operation is often needed if the operation is done on early age, because the nose has a restricted growth in the cleft area. Repair of the [[Ala of nose|ala]] (wing of the nose) often requires the inset of cartilage graft, commonly taken from the ear.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1288/00005537-198505000-00003 |pmid=3990484 |year=1985 |last1=Tardy |first1=M. Eugene |title=The Versatile Cartilage Autograft in Reconstruction of the Nose and Face |last2=Denneny |first2=James |last3=Fritsch |first3=Michael H. |journal=The Laryngoscope |volume=95 |issue=5 |pages=523\u2013533 }}</ref>\n\n=== Treatment of midface anomalies ===\nThe treatment of soft tissue parts of midface anomalies is often a reconstruction from a skin flap of the cheek. This skinflap can be used for other operations in the further, as it can be raised again and transposed again. In the treatment of midface anomalies there are generally more operations needed. Bone tissue reconstruction of the midface often occurs later than the soft tissue reconstruction. The most common method to reconstruct the midface is by using the fracture/ incision lines described by [[Ren\u00e9 Le Fort]]. When the cleft involves the maxilla, it is likely that the impaired growth will result in a smaller maxillary bone in all 3 dimensions (height, projection, width).\n\n=== Treatment of mouth anomalies ===\nThere are several options for treatment of mouth anomalies like Tessier cleft number 2-3-7 . These clefts are also seen in various syndromes like Treacher Collins syndrome and hemifacial microsomia, which makes the treatment much more complicated. In this case, treatment of mouth anomalies is a part of the treatment of the syndrome.\n\n== See also ==\n'''Related articles'''\n\n* [[Ectrodactyly\u2013ectodermal dysplasia\u2013cleft syndrome]]\n* [[Cleft hand]]\n* [[Cleft lip and palate]]\n\n'''Syndromes'''\n\n* [[Treacher Collins syndrome]]\n* [[Hemifacial microsomia]]\n* [[Goldenhar syndrome]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facial Cleft}}\n[[Category:Facial features]]\n[[Category:Oral and maxillofacial surgery]]\n[[Category:Congenital disorders]]\n", "text_old": "A '''facial cleft''' is an opening or gap in the [[face]], or a malformation of a part of the face. Facial clefts is a collective term for all sorts of clefts. All structures like bone, soft tissue, skin etc. can be affected. Facial clefts are extremely rare [[congenital anomalies]]. There are many variations of a type of clefting and classifications are needed to describe and classify all types of clefting. Facial clefts hardly ever occur isolated; most of the time there is an overlap of adjacent facial clefts.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=10332258 |year=1996 |last1=Moore |first1=MH |title=Rare craniofacial clefts |volume=7 |issue=6 |pages=408\u201311 |journal=The Journal of Craniofacial Surgery |doi=10.1097/00001665-199611000-00003}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n== Classifications ==\nThere are different classifications about facial clefts. Two of the most used classifications are the '''Tessier classification'''<ref>{{ cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0301-0503(76)80013-6 |pmid=820824 |title=Anatomical classification of facial, cranio-facial and latero-facial clefts |year=1976 |last1=Tessier |first1=P |journal=Journal of Maxillofacial Surgery |volume=4 |pages=69\u201392 |issue=2}}</ref> and the '''Van der Meulen classification'''.<ref name = \"Van der Meulen\">{{cite journal | author = Van der Meulen, JCH | title = Facial Clefts | journal = World J. Surg. | volume = 13 | pages = 373\u2013383 | year = 1989 |doi=10.1007/BF01660750| pmid =2773497 | issue = 4 | displayauthors = etal  }}</ref> Tessier is based on the anatomical position of the cleft and Van der Meulen classification is based on the embryogenesis.\n\n=== Tessier classification ===\n[[File:Picture Tessier classification.jpg|thumb|right|Tessier classification. Left: boney clefts, Right: Soft tissue clefts.]]\nIn 1976 [[Paul Tessier]] published a classification on facial clefts based on the anatomical position of the clefts. The different types of Tessier clefts are numbered 0 to 14. These 15 different types of clefts can be put into 4 groups, based on their position:<ref>Fearon, JA et al. \"Rare Craniofacial Clefts: A surgical Classification\", J Craniofac Surg. 2008 Jan;19(1):110-2,{{ cite journal |doi=10.1097/SCS.0b013e31815ca1ba| pmid=18216674 |year=2008 |last1=Fearon |first1=JA |title=Rare craniofacial clefts: a surgical classification |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=110\u20132 |journal=The Journal of Craniofacial Surgery }}</ref> midline clefts, paramedian clefts, orbital clefts and lateral clefts. The Tessier classification describes the clefts at soft tissue level as well as at bone level, because it appears that the soft tissue clefts can have a slightly different location on the face than the bony clefts.\n\n==== Midline clefts ====\nThe midline clefts are Tessier number 0 (\"median craniofacial dysplasia\"), number 14 ([[frontonasal dysplasia]]), and number 30 (\"lower midline facial cleft\", also known as \"median mandibular cleft\"). These clefts bisect the face vertically through the midline. Tessier number 0 bisects the [[maxilla]] and the nose, Tessier number 14 comes between the nose and the [[frontal bone]]. The Tessier number 30 facial cleft is through the tongue, lower lip and [[mandible]]. The tongue may be absent, hypoplastic, bifid, or even duplicated.<ref name=Bhattacharyya2012>{{cite journal|last=Bhattacharyya|first=NC|last2=Kalita|first2=K|last3=Gogoi|first3=M|last4=Deuri|first4=PK|title=Tessier 30 facial cleft|journal=Journal of Indian Association of Pediatric Surgeons|volume=17|issue=2|pages=75\u20137|year=2012|doi=10.4103/0971-9261.93970|pmc=3326828|pmid=22529554}}</ref> People with this condition may be [[Ankyloglossia|tongue-tied]].<ref name=Bhattacharyya2012/>\n\n==== Paramedian clefts ====\nTessier number 1, 2, 12 and 13 are the paramedian clefts. These clefts are quite similar to the midline clefts, but they are further away from the midline of the face. Tessier number 1 and 2 both come through the maxilla and the nose, in which Tessier number 2 is further from the midline ([[Lateral (anatomy)|lateral]]) than number 1. Tessier number 12 is in extent of number 2, positioned between nose and frontal bone, while Tessier number 13 is in extent of number 1, also running between nose and forehead. Both 12 and 13 run between the midline and the orbit.\n\n==== Orbital clefts ====\nTessier number 3, 4, 5, 9, 10 and 11 are orbital clefts. These clefts all have the involvement of the [[Orbit (anatomy)|orbit]]. Tessier number 3, 4, and 5 are positioned through the maxilla and the orbital floor. Tessier number 9, 10 and 11 are positioned between the upper side of the orbit and the forehead or between the upper side of the orbit and the [[temple]] of the head. \nLike the other clefts, Tessier number 11 is in extent to number 3, number 10 is in extent to number 4 and number 9 is in extent to number 5.\n\n==== Lateral clefts ====\nThe lateral clefts are the clefts which are positioned horizontally on the face. These are Tessier number 6, 7 and 8. Tessier number 6 runs from the orbit to the cheek bone. Tessier number 7 is positioned on the line between the corner of the mouth and the ear. A possible lateral cleft comes from the corner of the mouth towards the ear, which gives the impression that the mouth is bigger. It\u2019s also possible that the cleft begins at the ear and runs towards the mouth. Tessier number 8 runs from the outer corner of the eye towards the ear. \nThe combination of a Tessier number 6-7-8 is seen in the [[Treacher Collins syndrome]]. Tessier number 7 is more related to [[hemifacial microsomia]] and number 8 is more related to [[Goldenhar syndrome]].\n\n=== Van der Meulen classification ===\nVan der Meulen classification divides different types of clefts based on where the development arrest occurs in the [[embryogenesis]]. A primary cleft can occur in an early stage of the development of the face (17&nbsp;mm length of the embryo). The developments arrests can be divided in four different location groups: internasal, [[human nose|nasal]], nasalmaxillar and maxillar. The maxillar location can be subdivided in [[median]] and lateral clefts.\n \n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile: Van_der_meulen_-_internasal_dysplasia.jpg | Internasal dysplasia\nFile: Nasal_dysplasia.jpg | Nasal dysplasia\nFile: Nasalmaxillary_dysplasia.jpg | Nasomaxillary dysplasia\nFile: Maxillary_dysplasia.jpg | Maxillary dysplasia\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==== Internasal dysplasia ====\nInternasal [[dysplasia]] is caused by a development arrest before the union of the both nasal halves. These clefts are characterized by a median cleft lip, a median notch of the [[cupid's bow]] or a duplication of the labial [[frenulum]]. Besides the median cleft lip, [[hypertelorism]] can be seen in these clefts. Also sometimes there can be an underdevelopment of the [[premaxilla]].\n\n==== Nasal dysplasia ====\nNasal dysplasia or nasoschisis is caused by a development arrest of the lateral side of the nose, resulting in a cleft in one of the nasal halves. The nasal septum and cavity can be involved, though this is rare. Nasoschisis is also characterized by hypertelorism.\n\n==== Nasomaxillary dysplasia ====\nNasomaxillary dysplasia is caused by a development arrest at the junction of the lateral side of the nose and the maxilla, which results in a complete or non-complete cleft between the nose and the orbital floor (nasoocular cleft) or between the mouth, nose and the orbital floor (oronasal-ocular cleft). The development of the lip is normal.\n\n==== Maxillary dysplasia ====\nMaxillary dysplasia can manifest itself on two different locations in the maxilla: in the medial or the lateral part of the maxilla.\n* '''''Median maxillary dysplasia''''' is caused by a development failure of the medial part of the maxillary [[ossification center]]s. This results in secondary clefting of the lip, [[philtrum]] and palate. Clefting from the maxilla to the orbital floor has also been reported.\n* '''''Lateral maxillary dysplasia''''' is caused by a development failure of the lateral part of the maxillary ossification centers, which also results in secondary clefting of the lip and palate. Clefting of the lateral part of the lower eyelid is typical for lateral maxillary dysplasia.\n==Causes==\nIt is possible that facial clefts are caused by a disorder in the migration of [[neural crest cell]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/01.PRS.0000070971.95846.9C |pmid =12900623 |title=Common Craniofacial Anomalies: Facial Clefts and Encephaloceles |year=2003 |last1=Hunt |first1=Jeremy A. |last2=Hobar |first2=P. Craig |journal=Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery |volume=112 |issue=2 |pages=606\u2013616}}</ref>\n\nAnother theory is that facial clefts are caused by failure of the fusion process and failure of inwards growth of the [[mesoderm]].\n\nOther theories are that genetics play a part in the development of facial clefts<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3109/02844316709006555 |title=Genetic and Non-Genetic Factors in the Etiology of Facial Clefts |year=1967 |last1=Fogh-Andersen |first1=P. |journal=Scandinavian Journal of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery and Hand Surgery |volume=1 |pages=22\u201329}}</ref> or that they are caused by amniotic bands.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=6794056 |year=1981 |last1=Mayou |first1=BJ |last2=Fenton |first2=OM |title=Oblique facial clefts caused by amniotic bands |volume=68 |issue=5 |pages=675\u201381 |journal=Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery |doi=10.1097/00006534-198111000-00001}}</ref>\n\n=== Genetics ===\nAround one in 700 individuals are born with craniofacial clefts<ref name=\":1\">Leslie, E.J., and Marazita, M.L. (2013). Genetics of Cleft Lip and Cleft Palate. Am J Med Genet C Semin Med Genet 163, 246\u2013258.</ref>. There are multiple genetic and environmental factors which contribute to craniofacial development. Within craniofacial disorders and [[Craniofacial abnormality|abnormalities]], orofacial clefts, and specifically [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|cleft lip]] (CL) and [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|cleft palate]] (CP) are the most common in humans<ref name=\":1\" />. Occurrences of CL/P are most often (around seventy percent of cases) isolated and nonsyndromic, meaning they are not associated with a syndrome or inherited genetic conditions<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">Yoon, A.J., Pham, B.N., and Dipple, K.M. (2016). Genetic Screening in Patients with Craniofacial Malformations. J Pediatr Genet 5, 220\u2013224.</ref>. Around thirty percent occur with other structural variances, and over 500 syndromes have been identified in which clefting is a principal feature<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Clefting can result from [[Teratology|teratogens]], an agent that disrupts embryo development such as, radiation, maternal infection, chemicals, or drugs<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. [[Chromosome abnormality|Chromosomal abnormalities]] or [[Mutation|mutations]] at single gene loci have also contributed to clefting development<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Genetic causes are linked with most craniofacial syndromes, and CL/P and other orofacial clefts are recognized as [[Heterogeneous condition|heterogeneous disorders]], meaning there are multiple recognized causes<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">Cohen, M.M. (2002). Malformations of the craniofacial region: evolutionary, embryonic, genetic, and clinical perspectives. Am. J. Med. Genet. 115, 245\u2013268.</ref>. Orofacial clefts have great phenotypic diversity, and their associated genetic environments have called for vast research and investigation.\n\nCraniofacial disorders have high variance in phenotypic expression, and researchers have suggested this variance could be due to interactions between the mutated/deviated genes and other genes, along with interactions with environmental factors<ref name=\":4\">Weinberg, Seth M., Robert Cornell, and Elizabeth J. Leslie. 2018. \u201cCraniofacial Genetics: Where Have We Been and Where Are We Going?\u201d PLoS Genetics 14 (6): e1007438. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pgen.1007438.</ref><ref name=\":5\">Roosenboom, Jasmien, Greet Hens, Brooke C. Mattern, Mark D. Shriver, and Peter Claes. 2016. \u201cExploring the Underlying Genetics of Craniofacial Morphology through Various Sources of Knowledge.\u201d Edited by Ilker ERCAN. BioMed Research International 2016 (December): 3054578. https://doi.org/10.1155/2016/3054578.</ref>. Environmental causes have been found to contribute to craniofacial clefting, however, these are still influenced by and supported by genetic factors. Many studies, for example, have linked maternal smoking to increased CLP risk; however, the increased risk suggests that genes in metabolic pathways could still contribute to susceptibility or formation of CL/P<ref name=\":6\">Dixon, M.J., Marazita, M.L., Beaty, T.H., and Murray, J.C. (2011). Cleft lip and palate: synthesizing genetic and environmental influences. Nat Rev Genet 12, 167\u2013178.</ref>.\n\nThe craniofacial complex begins its progress in the fourth week of development, and results from [[neural crest]] cells migrating to form and fuse the facial primordia<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. Failures or deviations in this process result in craniofacial clefts, either CL or CP<ref name=\":0\" />. The range of variation in phenotype aligns with ancestry<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" />. Studies have found increased amounts of clefting in the relatives of patients with clefts, suggesting genetic factors are the underlying cause for CL/P<ref name=\":1\" />. Inheritance has a known and significant role in human craniofacial morphology. This is supported through cephalometric and anthropometric comparisons of family members including between triplets, twins, siblings, and parents and children<ref>The Role of Genetics in Craniofacial Morphology and Growth | Annual Review of Anthropology.</ref>.\n\nGenetic factors of craniofacial clefting can be investigated and tracked through several methods including [[sequencing]] in humans, [[Genome-wide association study|Genome-wide association studies]] (GWAs), [[fate mapping]], expression analysis, and animal studies (knockout experiments or models with clefting from chemical mutagenesis)<ref>Facebase.org</ref>. [[Twin study|Twin studies]] and familial clustering have also revealed that facial structure and formation are genetically linked. Several genes have been associated with craniofacial disorders through experimentation, inlcuding sequencing Mendelian clefting syndromes<ref name=\":1\" />. Over 25 loci have been identified as potential influencers of craniofacial clefts across populations<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\nThe [[transforming growth factor]] (''TGF'') family has provided multiple candidate genes linked with craniofacial development and malformation<ref name=\":7\">Genetic and Teratogenic Approaches To Craniofacial Development - D.L. Young, R.A. Schneider, D. Hu, J.A. Helms, 2000.</ref><ref name=\":8\">Wilkie, A.O., and Morriss-Kay, G.M. (2001). Genetics of craniofacial development and malformation. Nat. Rev. Genet. 2, 458\u2013468.</ref><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. ''TGF'' is involved in cell migration, differentiation, and proliferation, as well as regulating the extracellular matrix<ref name=\":7\" />. Another gene that has been flagged as causal for craniofacial disorders, including CL/P, is [[IRF6|interferon regulatory factor 6]] or, ''[[IRF6]]''<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\">SPECC1L deficiency results in increased adherens junction stability and reduced cranial neural crest cell delamination. - PubMed - NCBI.</ref>. Mutations in ''IRF6'' cause [[Van der Woude syndrome]], the most common clefting syndrome<ref name=\":1\" />. [[VAX1|Ventral anterior homeobox 1]], ''VAX1,'' and [[Noggin (protein)|noggin]], ''NOG'', were identified with genome-wide significance for contributing to CL/P<ref name=\":6\" />. Additionally, mutations in ''SPECC1L'' have recently been identified as influential to facial structure formation, and as causal for syndromic facial clefting<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Kruszka, P., Li, D., Harr, M.H., Wilson, N.R., Swarr, D., McCormick, E.M., Chiavacci, R.M., Li, M., Martinez, A.F., Hart, R.A., et al. (2015). Mutations in SPECC1L, encoding sperm antigen with calponin homology and coiled-coil domains 1-like, are found in some cases of autosomal dominant Opitz G/BBB syndrome. J. Med. Genet. 52, 104\u2013110.</ref>. Nonsyndromic CL/P has been associated with the transcription factor [[FOXE1|forkhead box protein E1]] (''FOXE1''), as mutations have resulted in cases of CL/P in mice<ref name=\":2\" />. Other genes which have been found to interact with or contribute to craniofacial clefting include ''FGFR''s, ''TWIST'', ''MSX''s, ''GREM1'', ''TCOF1'', ''PAX''s, ''MAFB'', ''ABCA4,'' and ''WNT'' allowing great cause for more research into the genetic basis for craniofacial disorders<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Prevention ==\nBecause the cause of facial clefts still is unclear, it is difficult to say what may prevent children being born with facial clefts. It seems that [[folic acid]] contributes to lowering the risk of a child being born with a facial cleft.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.39079.618287.0B |pmid=17259187 |title=Folic acid supplements and risk of facial clefts: national population based case-control study |year=2007 |last1=Wilcox |first1=A. J |last2=Lie |first2=R. T. |last3=Solvoll |first3=K. |last4=Taylor |first4=J. |last5=McConnaughey |first5=D R. |last6=Abyholm |first6=F. |last7=Vindenes |first7=H. |last8=Vollset |first8=S. E. |last9=Drevon |first9=C. A |journal=BMJ |volume=334 |issue=7591 |pages=464 |pmc=1808175  }}</ref>\n\n== Treatment ==\nThere is no single strategy for treatment of facial clefts, because of the large amount of variation in these clefts. Which kind of surgery is used depends on the type of clefting and which structures are involved. There is much discussion about the timing of reconstruction of bone and soft tissue. The problem with early reconstruction is the recurrence of the deformity due to the intrinsic restricted growth. This requires additional operations at a later age to make sure all parts of the face are in proportion.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.3109/02844318209006569 |pmid= 7051271|title=Adolescent Facial Morphology of Early Bone-Grafted Cleft Lip and Palate Patients|year=1982|last1=Friede|first1=Hans|last2=Johanson|first2=Bengt|journal=Scandinavian Journal of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery and Hand Surgery|volume=16|pages=41\u201353|issue=1}}</ref> A disadvantage of early bone reconstruction is the chance to damage the tooth germs, which are located in the maxilla, just under the orbit. The soft tissue reconstruction can be done at an early age, but only if the used skin flap can be used again during a second operation. The timing of the operation depends on the urgency of the underlying condition. If the operation is necessary to function properly, it should be done at early age. The best aesthetic result is achieved when the incisions are positioned in areas which attract the least attention (they cover up the scars). If, however, the function of a part of the face isn\u2019t damaged, the operation depends on psychological factors and the facial area of reconstruction. \n \nThe treatment plan of a facial cleft is planned right after diagnosis. This plan includes every operation needed in the first 18 years of the patients life to reconstruct the face fully. \nIn this plan, a difference is made between problems that need to be solved to improve the health of the patient (coloboma) and problems that need to be solved for a better cosmetic result (hypertelorism). \n \nThe treatment of the facial clefts can be divided in different areas of the face: the cranial anomalies, the orbital and eye anomalies, the nose anomalies, the midface anomalies and the mouth anomalies.\n\n=== Treatment of the cranial anomalies ===\nThe most common cranial anomaly seen in combination with facial clefts is [[encephalocele]].\n\n==== Encephalocele ====\nThe treatment of encephalocele is based on surgery to repair the bony gap and provide adequate protection of the underlying brain. The question remains if the external brain tissue should be put back into the skull or if it is possible to cut off that piece of brain tissue, because its claimed that the external piece of brain tissue often isn\u2019t functional,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1288/00005537-198208000-00008 |pmid= 7098736 |year=1982 |last1=Kamerer |first1=Donald B. |title= Temporal Bone Encephalocele ??? Diagnosis and Treatment |last2=Caparosa |first2=Ralph J. |journal=The Laryngoscope |volume=92 |issue=8 |pages=878\u2013882}}</ref> with the exception of a basal encephalocele, in which the pituitary gland can be found in the mouth.\n\n=== Treatment of orbital / eye anomalies ===\nThe most common orbital /eye anomalies seen in children with facial clefts are colobomas and vertical dystopia.\n\n==== Coloboma ====\nThe coloboma which occurs often in facial clefts is a cleft in the lower or upper eyelid. This should be closed as soon as possible, to prevent drought of the eye and a consecutive loss of vision.<ref>Patipa M et al., \"Surgical management of congenital eyelid coloboma\", Ophthalmic Surg. 1982 Mar;13(3):212-216 {{cite journal |pmid=7088491 |year=1982 |last1=Patipa |first1=M |last2=Wilkins |first2=RB |last3=Guelzow |first3=KW |title=Surgical management of congenital eyelid coloboma |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=212\u20136 |journal=Ophthalmic Surgery }}</ref>\n\n==== Vertical orbital dystopia ====\nVertical orbital dystopia can occur in facial clefts when the orbital floor and/or the maxilla is involved in the cleft. Vertical orbital dystopia means that the eyes do not lay on the same horizontal line in the face (one eye is positioned lower than the other). The treatment is based on the reconstruction of this orbital floor, by either closing the boney cleft or reconstructing the orbital floor using a [[bone graft]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/SCS.0b013e3181e57241 |pmid=20613583 |title=Orbital Floor Reconstruction |year=2010 |last1=Tabrizi |first1=Reza |last2=Ozkan |first2=Taha Birkan |last3=Mohammadinejad |first3=Cyrus |last4=Minaee |first4=Nasim |journal=Journal of Craniofacial Surgery |volume=21 |issue=4 |pages=1142\u20131146 }}</ref>\n\n==== Hypertelorism ====\nThere are many types of operations which can be performed to treat a hypertelorism. 2 options are: box osteotomy and facial bipartition<ref>Marchad D & Arnaud E, \"Midface surgery from Tessier to distraction\", Childs Nerv Syst. 1999 Nov;15(11-12):681-94, {{ cite journal |doi=10.1007/s003810050458 |pmid= 10603010 |title=Midface surgery from Tessier to distraction |year=1999 |last1=Marchac |first1=D. |last2=Arnaud |first2=Eric |journal=Child's Nervous System |volume=15 |issue=11\u201312 |pages=681\u2013694}}</ref> (also referred to as a median fasciotomy).\nThe goal of the box osteotomy is to bring the orbits closer together by removing a part of the bone between the orbits, to detach both orbits from the surrounding bone structures and move both orbits more to the centre of the face. \nThe goal of the facial bipartition is not only to bring the orbits closer together, but also to create more space in the maxilla. This can be done by splitting the maxilla and the frontal bone, remove a triangular shaped piece of bone from the forehead and nasal bones and pulling the two pieces of forehead together. Not only will the hypertelorism be solved by pulling the frontal bone closer together, but because of this pulling, the space between the both parts of the maxilla will become wider.\n<center>\n<gallery>\nFile: Picture_box_osteotomy.jpg|<center> Box Osteotomy </center>\nFile: Picture_median_fasciotomy.jpg | <center> Facial Bipartition </center>\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n=== Treatment of nose anomalies ===\nThe nose anomalies found in facial clefts vary. The main goal of the treatment is to reconstruct the nose to get a functional and esthetic acceptable result. A few possible treatment options are to reconstruct the nose with a forehead flap or reconstruct the nasal dorsum with a bone graft, for example a rib graft. The [[nasal reconstruction]] with a forehead flap is based on the repositioning of a skin flap from the forehead to the nose. A possible downside of this reconstruction is that once you performed it at a younger age, you can\u2019t lengthen the flap at a later stage. A second operation is often needed if the operation is done on early age, because the nose has a restricted growth in the cleft area. Repair of the [[Ala of nose|ala]] (wing of the nose) often requires the inset of cartilage graft, commonly taken from the ear.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1288/00005537-198505000-00003 |pmid=3990484 |year=1985 |last1=Tardy |first1=M. Eugene |title=The Versatile Cartilage Autograft in Reconstruction of the Nose and Face |last2=Denneny |first2=James |last3=Fritsch |first3=Michael H. |journal=The Laryngoscope |volume=95 |issue=5 |pages=523\u2013533 }}</ref>\n\n=== Treatment of midface anomalies ===\nThe treatment of soft tissue parts of midface anomalies is often a reconstruction from a skin flap of the cheek. This skinflap can be used for other operations in the further, as it can be raised again and transposed again. In the treatment of midface anomalies there are generally more operations needed. Bone tissue reconstruction of the midface often occurs later than the soft tissue reconstruction. The most common method to reconstruct the midface is by using the fracture/ incision lines described by [[Ren\u00e9 Le Fort]]. When the cleft involves the maxilla, it is likely that the impaired growth will result in a smaller maxillary bone in all 3 dimensions (height, projection, width).\n\n=== Treatment of mouth anomalies ===\nThere are several options for treatment of mouth anomalies like Tessier cleft number 2-3-7 . These clefts are also seen in various syndromes like Treacher Collins syndrome and hemifacial microsomia, which makes the treatment much more complicated. In this case, treatment of mouth anomalies is a part of the treatment of the syndrome.\n\n== See also ==\n'''Related articles'''\n\n* [[Ectrodactyly\u2013ectodermal dysplasia\u2013cleft syndrome]]\n* [[Cleft hand]]\n* [[Cleft lip and palate]]\n\n'''Syndromes'''\n\n* [[Treacher Collins syndrome]]\n* [[Hemifacial microsomia]]\n* [[Goldenhar syndrome]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facial Cleft}}\n[[Category:Facial features]]\n[[Category:Oral and maxillofacial surgery]]\n[[Category:Congenital disorders]]\n", "name_user": "Evalicht88", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGenetics:added subheadings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craniofacial_cleft"}
{"title_page": "Richard Carpenter (musician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Richard Carpenter}}\n{{short description|American pop musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Richard Carpenter\n| image               = Richard Carpenter - NARA - 194770.tif\n| caption             = Carpenter at the [[White House]] in August 1972\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1946|10|15|}}<ref name=\"birthdate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/biography-1.htm |website=Richardandp KarenCarpenter.com |title=Carpenters biography |date=2005}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = {{nowrap|[[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.}}\n| birth_name          = Richard Lynn Carpenter\n| origin              = [[Downey, California]], U.S.\n| genre               = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| instrument          = {{hlist|Vocals|[[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1969\u2013present<ref name=\"A&M\">{{harvnb|Schmidt|2012|p=1903}}</ref>\n| occupation          = Musician, record producer, arranger, songwriter, conductor\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[The Carpenters]]|[[Karen Carpenter]]}}\n| website             = {{url|http://richardandkarencarpenter.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Richard Lynn Carpenter''' (born  October 15, 1946) is an American musician, record producer, songwriter, and music arranger, who formed half of the sibling duo [[The Carpenters]] alongside his sister [[Karen Carpenter|Karen]]. He has had numerous roles including record producer, arranger, pianist, keyboardist, lyricist, and composer, as well as joining with Karen on harmony vocals.\n\n==Childhood==\nRichard Lynn Carpenter was born at [[Grace-New Haven Hospital]] (now called Yale-New Haven Hospital) in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], the same hospital where his sister Karen was later born.<ref>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|ps=; Forward, [[Dionne Warwick]]}}</ref> His parents were Agnes Reuwer Tatum (a housewife<ref name=\"Gavin, James\">{{cite news|work=The New York Times Book Review|title=Sorrow in Her Voice|author=Gavin, James|date=August 6, 2010}}</ref>) (March 5, 1915 \u2013 November 10, 1996) and Harold Bertram Carpenter (November 8, 1908 \u2013 October 15, 1988). His father was born in [[China]], where his own parents were missionaries, and was educated at boarding schools in [[England]],<ref name=\"Schmidt2010\">{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010}}</ref> before working in the printing business.<ref name=\"Gavin, James\"/> Carpenter was named after his father's younger brother, Richard Lynn Carpenter. Carpenter and his uncle both married women named Mary.<ref>{{cite book| author=Coleman, Ray| title= The Carpenters: The Untold Story| url=https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole| url-access=registration|date=1994| page= [https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole/page/30 30]}}</ref> Richard and his sister were baptized into the [[United Methodist Church]] and as children were part of the Methodist Youth Ministry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wyI4_Phue4IC&pg=RA2-PT146&dq=karen+carpenter+methodist&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9gJ3u1sjXAhWDWRoKHTwjDCAQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=karen+carpenter+methodist&f=falseYesterday|title=Yesterday Once More: The Carpenters Reader|first=Randy L.|last=Schmidt|date=12 April 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter frequently played the piano while his younger sister, [[Karen Carpenter|Karen]], played baseball outside.<ref name=cty>Close to You: Remembering the Carpenters</ref> He and Karen also liked to listen to the children's records their father bought for them when they were young.<ref name=cty/> Richard was introduced to [[Perry Como]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], among many others through his father's record collection,<ref name=Billboard>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FAkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA13&dq=the+carpenters&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=the%20carpenters&f=false|title=A Talented Brother and Sister Act Which Represents Clean, Wholesome Entertainment|author=Lieberman, Frank H.|work=Billboard|page=C-6|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=November 17, 1973|issn= 0006-2510|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  and by age 12, he knew he wanted to be in the music industry. His first public appearance as a musician was at age 16 in New Haven. Along with two older friends, a group was formed and they played at a local pizza parlor.  Richard joined the venture to earn money to buy a car.<ref name=Billboard/>  The Carpenter family moved from New Haven to [[Downey, California]], in June 1963. They wanted Richard to further his music career, and the family was tired of the cold [[New England]] winters.<ref>{{cite book|author=Coleman, Ray|title= The Carpenters: The Untold Story|url=https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole|url-access=registration|date= 1994|page= [https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole/page/48 48]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.npr.org/2013/02/04/171080334/remembering-karen-carpenter-30-years-later|title=Remembering Karen Carpenter, 30 Years Later|author=Samberg, Joel|date=February 4, 2013|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter studied music at [[California State University, Long Beach|California State College at Long Beach]] (now known as California State University, Long Beach). There, he met [[Frank Pooler]], a conductor and composer who wrote the lyrics to the Christmas classic \"[[Merry Christmas Darling]]\" in 1968. Richard also met good friend, [[John Bettis]], who co-wrote songs with Richard.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=2017-03-18 |url=http://nashvillesongwritersfoundation.com/Site/inductee?entry_id=1678 |title=John Bettis|publisher=Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame}}</ref> At Long Beach Richard also met Gary Sims, Dan Woodhams, and Doug Strawn, who would later become members of the Carpenters\u2019 live band.\n\n==The Richard Carpenter Trio, Spectrum and Summerchimes==\nCarpenter created the Richard Carpenter Trio in 1965 with sister Karen and friend Wes Jacobs. Richard played the piano, Karen played the drums, and Wes played the tuba and bass.\n\nIn 1966 the Richard Carpenter Trio played \"Iced Tea\" and \"[[The Girl from Ipanema]]\" at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] [[Battle of the Bands]]. They won the competition, and shortly afterward recorded three songs at [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]]: \"[[Every Little Thing (Beatles song)|Every Little Thing]]\", \"[[Strangers in the Night]]\", and the Carpenter original, \"Iced Tea\". \"Iced Tea\" is the only recording that was officially released to the public.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nAround 1967 Richard and Karen joined four other student musicians from [[California State University, Long Beach|Long Beach State]] to form a sextet, '''Spectrum''', consisting of:\n*Richard Carpenter\n*Karen Carpenter\n*[[John Bettis]]\n*Leslie Johnston\n*Gary Sims\n*Danny Woodhams\n\nAlthough Spectrum played frequently at LA-area nightclubs such as [[Whisky a Go Go]], they met with an unenthusiastic response\u2014their broad harmonies and avoidance of [[Rock and roll|rock 'n' roll]] limited the band's commercial potential. Yet Spectrum was fruitful in another way, providing the raw material of future success: Bettis went on to become a lyricist for Richard's original compositions, and all the other members, except Leslie Johnston, went on to become members of the Carpenters.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}.  Following on from Spectrum, Carpenter formed ''Summerchimes''.  In a similar vein to ''Spectrum'', the group was also short lived but produced such fruits as \"Don't be Afraid\", \"All of My Life\" and several other songs which appeared on the Carpenters' debut album.\n\n==Career==\nRichard and Karen signed with [[A&M Records]] on April 22, 1969. \"Let's hope we have some hits,\" [[Herb Alpert]] told the two. According to Richard, Alpert gave them artistic freedom in the recording studios, but after ''[[Ticket to Ride (album)|Offering]]'', their first album, was released and wasn't a big seller, it was rumored that some of A&M's people were asking Alpert to release the Carpenters, but he believed in their talent and insisted on giving them another chance.\n\nAlpert suggested that the Carpenters record a [[Burt Bacharach]] and [[Hal David]] song called \"[[(They Long to Be) Close to You]]\" written in 1963. Though Richard worked up an arrangement only after Alpert's insistence, his arranging talents clearly shone in the finished product. His arranging and musical talents, as well as Karen's vocals, helped the song climb to #1 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], where it stayed for a month. \"(They Long to Be) Close to You\" gained public recognition seemingly overnight. According to Richard, even though the song became popular overnight, the Carpenters themselves did not.\n\nSitting at home one night, Richard was watching TV and saw a commercial for [[Crocker National Bank]]. He recognized the voices of [[Paul Williams (songwriter)|Paul Williams]] and [[Roger Nichols (songwriter)|Roger Nichols]], two A&M songwriters on the commercial's theme song \"[[We've Only Just Begun]].\" Richard made some calls to confirm their involvement, and asked if there was a full version of the song, which Williams affirmed. Carpenter managed to turn the bank commercial jingle into an [[RIAA certification|RIAA-certified]] [[Music recording sales certification|Gold record]]. It peaked at #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and has become a popular wedding song. The song also successfully launched the careers of Nichols and Williams, who went on to write multiple hits for the Carpenters and many other artists.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nRichard composed many of the Carpenters' hits as well, with John Bettis as lyricist, such as:\n*\"[[Goodbye to Love]]\" (1972; #7; one of the first pop ballads to have a [[fuzz guitar]] solo\u2014influenced the development of the [[power ballad]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Popular Musicians| authors=Hochman, Steve Hochman & Adams, Mcrea |date= 1999 |page =168 }}</ref>)\n*\"[[Top of the World (The Carpenters song)|Top of the World]]\" (1972; #1. Though the Carpenters originally opted to not release this song as a single, a version recorded by [[Lynn Anderson]] reached #2 on the ''Billboard'' Country chart; following the success of Anderson's version, the Carpenters decided to release their version as a single, and it reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.)\n*\"[[Yesterday Once More (song)|Yesterday Once More]]\" (1973; #2)\n*\"[[Only Yesterday (song)|Only Yesterday]]\" (1975; #4)\n\n==Quaalude addiction and treatment==\nWhile Karen was suffering from the [[anorexia nervosa]] that would ultimately lead to her death in 1983, in the late 1970s, Richard suffered from insomnia, panic attacks, depression, and an addiction to [[Methaqualone|Quaalude]], a sedative and hypnotic medication. Author James Gavin noted in his ''New York Times'' review of Randy L. Schmidt's biography ''Little Girl Blue: The Life of Karen Carpenter'' (2010):<ref name=\"Schmidt2010\"/> \"His mother is said to have given him his first pill,\"<ref name=\"Gavin, James\"/> an observation that was previously portrayed in the [[CBS|CBS-TV]]  television film ''[[The Karen Carpenter Story]]'' (1989) and commented on in several of that [[Television film|made-for-TV]] movie's reviews, which also noted that Agnes (their mother) had been taking them under prescription and thus thought they were safe.<ref>{{cite news|author=Weiskind, Ron|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19881231&id=RbBRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=920DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6856,8508274|title=Why: Missing From Carpenter Story|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 31, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\">{{cite news|author=Sanello, Frank|date=January 1, 1989|title=`A Puzzle For The Ages`: Film Chronicles Carpenter`s Fall But Can`t Answer Why|work=The Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-01-01/features/8902220490_1_karen-carpenter-story-mrs-carpenter-anorexia-nervosa}}</ref> At the time he sought help, Carpenter had a doctor's prescription for Quaalude as a sleep aid, but his use had gotten out of hand.\n\nA reviewer of the [[BBC]] biopic ''[[Only Yesterday: The Carpenters Story]]'' (2007) notes: \"As their fame grew, cracks began to show in their wholesome facade. An insane touring schedule began to take its toll and Richard took refuge in heroic doses of quaaludes. Meanwhile, Karen started worrying about her weight. The worrying became obsession. The cracks became faultlines. The centre could not hold.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aerialtelly.co.uk/only-yesterday.php| work=Aerial Telly| date=April 11, 2007| author=jamdog| title=Only Yesterday \u2013 The Carpenters Story}}</ref>\n\nDr. Gabe Mirkin wrote in \"The sad story of Karen Carpenter\" (February 15, 2014), \"In those years, you could tell that something was wrong because the Carpenters frequently cancelled appearances. She appeared unhealthily thin, weighing only 90 pounds when she was 25. Richard appeared to be forgetful, and it was later found that he was addicted to Quaaludes. In 1978, the Carpenters stopped touring and in 1979 Richard went into treatment to cure his dependency on this drug.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Mirkin, Dr. Gabe|work=Village-News|url=http://www.villages-news.com/sad-story-karen-carpenter/|date=February 15, 2014|title=The sad story of Karen Carpenter}}</ref>\n\nNick Talevski similarly observes in ''Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking on Heaven's Door'' (2010): \"Constantly on the road since 1970 with their [[Las Vegas|Vegas]]-style act, both Karen and Richard Carpenter were in ill health by late 1975. With Karen's weight down to 80 pounds, a tour had to be cancelled. Richard, meanwhile, had become addicted to a prescription drug, Quaalude.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Talevski, Nick|title=Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking on Heaven's Door|publisher=Omnibus Press|date=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DykffzkFALoC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=richard+carpenter+has+prescription+for+quaaludes&source=bl&ots=6yrWMHwrZT&sig=oE_iljf_xrmuMFB2AapIwPz8UuI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ctECVJXOIo3NggTi_4GgAg&ved=0CFQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20carpenter%20has%20prescription%20for%20quaaludes&f=false}}</ref>\n\nBy late 1978, Richard was receiving \"much encouragement (and browbeating) from family and friends, to \u2018face the music.\u2019\"<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web| url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/biography-9.htm| page=9| title=Biography| website=RichardAndKarenCarpenter.com| accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref> Finally, in January 1979, semicomatose on Quaaludes, Richard fell down a flight of stairs backstage and finally confronted his addiction.\"<ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\"/> He checked into a six-week [[Drug rehabilitation|treatment]] program<ref name=\"Biography\"/> at the [[Menninger Foundation|Menninger Clinic]] in [[Topeka, Kansas]], and kicked his habit.<ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\"/> \"For any number of reasons, the first three weeks were 'hell on earth,' Richard says, 'but after that, things really started to change, and of course, all for the better.' Still, all of this had been a monumental change for Richard and he decided it was wise not to delve right back into work, and to pretty much take the rest of 1979 off, all the better to get accustomed to his changed fortunes.\"<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n\n==Post-Carpenters==\n[[File:Carpenters - Walk of Fame.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Carpenters' star at the Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n\nOn October 12, 1983, eight months after Karen's death, the Carpenter family celebrated the unveiling of The Carpenters' new star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. Carpenter said in his speech, \"This is a sad day, but at the same time a very special and beautiful day to my family and [me]. My only regret is that Karen is not physically here to share it with us, but I know that she is very much alive in our minds, and in our hearts.\"<ref name=cty/><ref>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|loc=[https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm/page/292 p.292]}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 1986, Carpenter started recording the solo album ''[[Time (Richard Carpenter album)|Time]]'' and finished it on July 5, 1987.<ref>''Time,'' Richard Carpenter. \"Recording for this album commenced on June 26, 1985, with the final session in mix-down occurring on July 5, 1987.\"</ref> The album features [[Dusty Springfield]] singing \"[[Something in Your Eyes (Richard Carpenter song)|Something in Your Eyes]]\", [[Dionne Warwick]] singing \"In Love Alone\", [[Scott Grimes]] singing \"That's What I Believe\" and a song Richard created \u2013 dedicated to Karen \u2013 called \"When Time Was All We Had\", which starts off [[a cappella]], but then Richard's piano fades in as well as [[Herb Alpert]]'s [[flugelhorn]]. Lyrics include:\n\n:Our hearts were filled with music and laughter,\n:Your voice will be the sweetest sound I'll ever hear and yet,\n:We knew somehow the song would never end,\n:When time was all we had to spend.\n\nIn 1996, at the suggestion of music writer [[Daniel Levitin]], Carpenter recorded and released ''Richard Carpenter: Pianist, Arranger, Composer, Conductor'', which included reworkings of many Carpenters favorites, including hits and album tracks, and ends with \"Karen's Theme\", which Carpenter composed for the television film ''The Karen Carpenter Story'' (1989).\n\nCarpenter released the DVDs ''[[Gold: Greatest Hits (video)|Gold: Greatest Hits]]'' (2002), a repackaging of the [[VHS]]/[[Betamax]] ''Yesterday Once More'' (released in 1985, two years after Karen's death in 1983) that contains all the videos from ''Yesterday Once More'', and ''[[Interpretations (The Carpenters DVD)|Interpretations]]'' (2003), which updates the original, VHS/cassette tape released in 1995 and includes footage from the Carpenters' five TV specials and TV series from 1971\u20131980. The DVD follows the compilation album of the same name, which had been released earlier the same year, and includes eleven Carpenters' tracks never before available on DVD (including \"From This Moment On\", an outtake from the Carpenters' fifth television special), all of them digitally enhanced and remastered in stereo audio.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=A&M|authors=Carpenter, Richard & Carpenter, Karen|date= July 29, 2003|asin= B0000A9D2F|url=https://www.amazon.com/Carpenters-Interpretations/dp/B0000A9D2F/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1409460224&sr=8-2&keywords=interpretations%2Cthe+carpenters|title=Capenters \u2013 Interpretations}}</ref>\n\nOn his 62nd birthday in October 2008, at a luncheon for The Foreign Correspondents Club of Japan, Carpenter announced plans for \"his career comeback \u2013 dubbed 'Richard Carpenter Strikes Back'\"\u2014which included \"the re-release of a Carpenters Christmas album and a tribute album featuring cover versions of Carpenters songs.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Carpenter ready to make a comeback |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/richard-carpenter-ready-to-make-a-comeback-1.334069 |website=CTV News |publisher=Associated Press |language=en |date=October 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=October 2008| website=Smooth Radio| title=Take a Look At Carpenters In Pictures: Richard Carpenter \u2013 a comeback?| url =http://www.smoothradio.com/artists/carpenters/carpenters-pictures/richard-carpenter-a-comeback/| author=AP Photo}}</ref>\n\n===Documentaries===\nThe 43-minute film ''[[Superstar: The Karen Carpenter Story]]'' (1987) was directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and was withdrawn from circulation in 1990, after Haynes lost a [[copyright infringement]] lawsuit filed by Richard.<ref name=\"holden\">{{cite news|author=[[Holden]], Stephen |date=November 8, 1998|title=FILM; Focusing on Glam Rock's Blurring of Identity|work=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> The film's title is derived from [[The Carpenters]]' 1971 hit song, \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)#Carpenters version|Superstar]].\"  Over the years, it has developed into a [[cult film]] and is included in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s 2003 list of top 50 cult movies.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dirks, Tim|url=http://www.filmsite.org/cultfilmsew2.html|title=Top 50 Cult Movies|work= [[Entertainment Weekly]]/[[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]|accessdate= January 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter helped in the productions of the documentaries ''[[Close to You: Remembering the Carpenters]]'' (1997) and ''[[Only Yesterday: The Carpenters Story]]'' (2007).\n\n===Scholarship/talent show===\nCarpenter funds an annual scholarship/talent show for people with artistic abilities that is held at the Thousand Oaks Civic Center.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n===Gear===\nCarpenter used a wide range of keyboard instruments including [[grand piano]], [[Hammond organ]], [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], [[ARP Odyssey]], [[Rhodes piano|Fender Rhodes electric piano]], [[harpsichord]], [[celesta]], [[synthesizer]] and [[tack piano]]. His favourite grand piano was [[Baldwin Piano Company|Baldwin]]. In the '70s, he initially endorsed and used Wurlitzer electric pianos before switching to the [[Rhodes piano|Fender Rhodes electric piano]]. He says that at [[A&M Studios]], he regularly used a [[Steinway]] piano on the Carpenters' records with the exception of the ''[[A Song for You (The Carpenters album)|A Song for You]]'' album in which he played a Baldwin piano which was autographed by Liberace. On stage, he had both a Wurlitzer electric piano and grand piano, but after switching to the Fender Rhodes, he would simply alternate between the three for different songs on stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/fans_ask_Archive-All.htm|title=Carpenters Fans Ask-Richard Answers Archive|website=www.richardandkarencarpenter.com}}</ref> He has described the sound of the Wurlitzer electric piano as \"warm\" and \"beautiful\" and via [[overdubbing]] in the studio, he would regularly supplement his grand piano with a Wurlitzer electric piano to thicken the sound, thus creating a distinctive keyboard sound. On the song \"Happy\" on ''[[Horizon (The Carpenters album)|Horizon]],'' he made his earliest experiments with the [[ARP Odyssey]] synthesizer.<ref>John Tobler. ''The Complete Guide to the Music of the Carpenters'' (1997); Omnibus Press, London; {{ISBN|0-7119-6312-6}};  p.67</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2014}}\nIn 1984, Carpenter married his adopted cousin, Mary Rudolph.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoerburger|first1=Rob|title=Karen Carpenter's Second Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/06/magazine/karen-carpenter-s-second-life.html?pagewanted=3|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=4 August 2015|quote=[I]n 1984, the year after Karen died, he married his cousin Mary Rudolph and is now the father of four.}}</ref> Her brother, Mark Rudolph, was the Carpenters' [[road manager]] as well as the radio call-in \"contestant\" in the [Oldies] \"Medley\" on the album ''[[Now & Then (The Carpenters album)|Now & Then]]'' (1973). The couple had been dating since the late 1970s. A young Mary made a cameo appearance in the Carpenters' promotional video for the song \"[[I Need to Be in Love]]\" (1976).\n\nRichard and Mary Carpenter have five children: Kristi Lynn (the name Karen would have given to a daughter) was born on August 17, 1987; Traci Tatum on July 25, 1989; Mindi Karen (named after her late paternal aunt) on July 7, 1992; Collin Paul on July 20, 1994; and Taylor Mary on December 5, 2000.<ref name=pp297>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|loc=[https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm/page/297 pp.297\u2013298]}}</ref> Today the family resides in [[Thousand Oaks, California]], and Richard and the children sometimes perform music together at various Carpenter-related events.<ref name=pp297/>\n\nCarpenter is a [[Mopar]] automobile enthusiast, and original owner of a 1970 [[Plymouth Barracuda]] with the unusual 440+6 V8 engine and automatic transmission package.<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Carpenter's 1970 Chrysler Barracuda|url=http://www.nbc.com/jay-lenos-garage/video/richard-carpenters-1970-chrysler-barracuda/310108|website=Jay Leno's Garage|accessdate=21 September 2016|date=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n=== The Carpenters ===\n{{Main|The Carpenters discography|List of songs recorded by The Carpenters}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"33\"| Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1987\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Time (Richard Carpenter album)|Time]]'''''\n| \n* Released in October 1987\n* Richard Carpenter's debut solo album\n* Included guest singers [[Dusty Springfield]], [[Dionne Warwick]], and actor [[Scott Grimes]]\n* Out of print\n* Label: [[A&M Records]]\n* Formats: [[LP album]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette tape]], [[Compact Disc|compact disc]], digital download\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 Composer \u2022 Conductor|Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 <br>Composer \u2022 Conductor]]'''''\n| \n* Released on January 27, 1998\n* Richard's second and latest solo album\n* Includes instrumentals of popular songs of Carpenters\n* Dedicated to Richard's deceased mother, Agnes Carpenter<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web |url= http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/|title= Richard and Karen Carpenter \u2013 Official website|accessdate=2008-01-17 |author= Carpenter, Richard}}</ref>\n* Label: A&M Records\n* Formats: Cassette tape (out of print), compact disc (out of print), digital download\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Song\n!colspan=\"6\"|Chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"|B-side\n!rowspan=\"2\"|<sup>[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]<br>cert.</sup><ref name=\"riaas\">{{cite web |url= https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Carpenters&format=SINGLE&go=Search&perPage=50|title=RIAA Gold and Platinum Search for singles by the Carpenters|accessdate=2008-07-03}}</ref>\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. Hot 100]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Adult Contemporary (chart)|U.S. AC]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Canadian Singles Chart|CAN]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Oricon Singles Chart|JPN]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</sup>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1987\n|\"[[Something in Your Eyes (Richard Carpenter song)|Something in Your Eyes]]\"<br><small>''(featuring [[Dusty Springfield]])''</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|84\n|<small>\"Time\"</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''Time''\n|-\n|\"Calling Your Name Again\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\"When Time Was All We Had\"</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1998\n|\"Karen's Theme\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\u2014</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 Composer \u2022 Conductor''\n|-\n|\"Medley\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\u2014</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Randy|title=Little Girl Blue: The Life Of Karen Carpenter|year=2010|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-1-556-52976-4|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/ Richard and Karen Carpenter Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|0139443|name=Richard Carpenter}}\n*[http://www.myokom.info/ Make Your Own Kind of Music] \u2013 1971 Summer Television Series\n\n{{The Carpenters albums}}\n\n{{Portal| Biography }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carpenter, Richard}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:A&M Records artists]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop pianists]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American Methodists]]\n[[Category:American soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Downey, California]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters members]]\n[[Category:California State University, Long Beach alumni]]\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:American pop keyboardists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Richard Carpenter}}\n{{short description|American pop musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Richard Carpenter\n| image               = Richard Carpenter - NARA - 194770.tif\n| caption             = Carpenter at the [[White House]] in August 1972\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1946|10|15|}}<ref name=\"birthdate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/biography-1.htm |website=Richardandp KarenCarpenter.com |title=Carpenters biography |date=2005}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = {{nowrap|[[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.}}\n| birth_name          = Richard Lynn Carpenter\n| origin              = [[Downey, California]], U.S.\n| genre               = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| instrument          = {{hlist|Vocals|[[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active        = 1969\u2013present<ref name=\"A&M\">{{harvnb|Schmidt|2012|p=1903}}</ref>\n| occupation          = Musician, record producer, arranger, songwriter, conductor\n| label               = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[The Carpenters]]|[[Karen Carpenter]]}}\n| website             = {{url|http://richardandkarencarpenter.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Richard Lynn Carpenter''' (born  October 15, 1946) is an American musician, record producer, songwriter, and music arranger, who formed half of the sibling duo [[The Carpenters]] alongside his sister [[Karen Carpenter|Karen]]. He has had numerous roles including record producer, arranger, pianist, keyboardist, lyricist, and composer, as well as joining with Karen on harmony vocals.\n\n==Childhood==\nRichard Lynn Carpenter was born at [[Grace-New Haven Hospital]] (now called Yale-New Haven Hospital) in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], the same hospital where his sister Karen was later born.<ref>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|ps=; Forward, [[Dionne Warwick]]}}</ref> His parents were Agnes Reuwer Tatum (a housewife<ref name=\"Gavin, James\">{{cite news|work=The New York Times Book Review|title=Sorrow in Her Voice|author=Gavin, James|date=August 6, 2010}}</ref>) (March 5, 1915 \u2013 November 10, 1996) and Harold Bertram Carpenter (November 8, 1908 \u2013 October 15, 1988). His father was born in [[China]], where his own parents were missionaries, and was educated at boarding schools in [[England]],<ref name=\"Schmidt2010\">{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010}}</ref> before working in the printing business.<ref name=\"Gavin, James\"/> Carpenter was named after his father's younger brother, Richard Lynn Carpenter. Carpenter and his uncle both married women named Mary.<ref>{{cite book| author=Coleman, Ray| title= The Carpenters: The Untold Story| url=https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole| url-access=registration|date=1994| page= [https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole/page/30 30]}}</ref> Richard and his sister were baptized into the [[United Methodist Church]] and as children were part of the Methodist Youth Ministry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wyI4_Phue4IC&pg=RA2-PT146&dq=karen+carpenter+methodist&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi9gJ3u1sjXAhWDWRoKHTwjDCAQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=karen+carpenter+methodist&f=falseYesterday|title=Yesterday Once More: The Carpenters Reader|first=Randy L.|last=Schmidt|date=12 April 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter frequently played the piano while his younger sister, [[Karen Carpenter|Karen]], played baseball outside.<ref name=cty>Close to You: Remembering the Carpenters</ref> He and Karen also liked to listen to the children's records their father bought for them when they were young.<ref name=cty/> Richard was introduced to [[Perry Como]] and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], among many others through his father's record collection,<ref name=Billboard>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FAkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA13&dq=the+carpenters&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=the%20carpenters&f=false|title=A Talented Brother and Sister Act Which Represents Clean, Wholesome Entertainment|author=Lieberman, Frank H.|work=Billboard|page=C-6|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=November 17, 1973|issn= 0006-2510|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  and by age 12, he knew he wanted to be in the music industry. His first public appearance as a musician was at age 16 in New Haven. Along with two older friends, a group was formed and they played at a local pizza parlor.  Richard joined the venture to earn money to buy a car.<ref name=Billboard/>  The Carpenter family moved from New Haven to [[Downey, California]], in June 1963. They wanted Richard to further his music career, and the family was tired of the cold [[New England]] winters.<ref>{{cite book|author=Coleman, Ray|title= The Carpenters: The Untold Story|url=https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole|url-access=registration|date= 1994|page= [https://archive.org/details/carpentersuntold00cole/page/48 48]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|\nurl=https://www.npr.org/2013/02/04/171080334/remembering-karen-carpenter-30-years-later|title=Remembering Karen Carpenter, 30 Years Later|author=Samberg, Joel|date=February 4, 2013|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter studied music at [[California State University, Long Beach|California State College at Long Beach]] (now known as California State University, Long Beach). There, he met [[Frank Pooler]], a conductor and composer who wrote the lyrics to the Christmas classic \"[[Merry Christmas Darling]]\" in 1968. Richard also met good friend, [[John Bettis]], who co-wrote songs with Richard.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=2017-03-18 |url=http://nashvillesongwritersfoundation.com/Site/inductee?entry_id=1678 |title=John Bettis|publisher=Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame}}</ref> At Long Beach Richard also met Gary Sims, Dan Woodhams, and Doug Strawn, who would later become members of the Carpenters\u2019 live band.\n\n==The Richard Carpenter Trio, Spectrum and Summerchimes==\nCarpenter created the Richard Carpenter Trio in 1965 with sister Karen and friend Wes Jacobs. Richard played the piano, Karen played the drums, and Wes played the tuba and bass.\n\nIn 1966 the Richard Carpenter Trio played \"Iced Tea\" and \"[[The Girl from Ipanema]]\" at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] [[Battle of the Bands]]. They won the competition, and shortly afterward recorded three songs at [[RCA Records|RCA Studios]]: \"[[Every Little Thing (Beatles song)|Every Little Thing]]\", \"[[Strangers in the Night]]\", and the Carpenter original, \"Iced Tea\". \"Iced Tea\" is the only recording that was officially released to the public.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nAround 1967 Richard and Karen joined four other student musicians from [[California State University, Long Beach|Long Beach State]] to form a sextet, '''Spectrum''', consisting of:\n*Richard Carpenter\n*Karen Carpenter\n*[[John Bettis]]\n*Leslie Johnston\n*Gary Sims\n*Danny Woodhams\n\nAlthough Spectrum played frequently at LA-area nightclubs such as [[Whisky a Go Go]], they met with an unenthusiastic response\u2014their broad harmonies and avoidance of [[Rock and roll|rock 'n' roll]] limited the band's commercial potential. Yet Spectrum was fruitful in another way, providing the raw material of future success: Bettis went on to become a lyricist for Richard's original compositions, and all the other members, except Leslie Johnston, went on to become members of the Carpenters.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}.  Following on from Spectrum, Carpenter formed ''Summerchimes''.  In a similar vein to ''Spectrum'', the group was also short lived but produced such fruits as \"Don't be Afraid\", \"All of My Life\" and several other songs which appeared on the Carpenters' debut album.\n\n==Career==\nRichard and Karen signed with [[A&M Records]] on April 22, 1969. \"Let's hope we have some hits,\" [[Herb Alpert]] told the two. According to Richard, Alpert gave them artistic freedom in the recording studios, but after ''[[Ticket to Ride (album)|Offering]]'', their first album, was released and wasn't a big seller, it was rumored that some of A&M's people were asking Alpert to release the Carpenters, but he believed in their talent and insisted on giving them another chance.\n\nAlpert suggested that the Carpenters record a [[Burt Bacharach]] and [[Hal David]] song called \"[[(They Long to Be) Close to You]]\" written in 1963. Though Richard worked up an arrangement only after Alpert's insistence, his arranging talents clearly shone in the finished product. His arranging and musical talents, as well as Karen's vocals, helped the song climb to #1 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], where it stayed for a month. \"(They Long to Be) Close to You\" gained public recognition seemingly overnight. According to Richard, even though the song became popular overnight, the Carpenters themselves did not.\n\nSitting at home one night, Richard was watching TV and saw a commercial for [[Crocker National Bank]]. He recognized the voices of [[Paul Williams (songwriter)|Paul Williams]] and [[Roger Nichols (songwriter)|Roger Nichols]], two A&M songwriters on the commercial's theme song \"[[We've Only Just Begun]].\" Richard made some calls to confirm their involvement, and asked if there was a full version of the song, which Williams affirmed. Carpenter managed to turn the bank commercial jingle into an [[RIAA certification|RIAA-certified]] [[Music recording sales certification|Gold record]]. It peaked at #2 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and has become a popular wedding song. The song also successfully launched the careers of Nichols and Williams, who went on to write multiple hits for the Carpenters and many other artists.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nRichard composed many of the Carpenters' hits as well, with John Bettis as lyricist, such as:\n*\"[[Goodbye to Love]]\" (1972; #7; one of the first pop ballads to have a [[fuzz guitar]] solo\u2014influenced the development of the [[power ballad]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Popular Musicians| authors=Hochman, Steve Hochman & Adams, Mcrea |date= 1999 |page =168 }}</ref>)\n*\"[[Top of the World (The Carpenters song)|Top of the World]]\" (1972; #1. Though the Carpenters originally opted to not release this song as a single, a version recorded by [[Lynn Anderson]] reached #2 on the ''Billboard'' Country chart; following the success of Anderson's version, the Carpenters decided to release their version as a single, and it reached number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.)\n*\"[[Yesterday Once More (song)|Yesterday Once More]]\" (1973; #2)\n*\"[[Only Yesterday (song)|Only Yesterday]]\" (1975; #4)\n\n==Quaalude addiction and treatment==\nWhile Karen was suffering from the [[anorexia nervosa]] that would ultimately lead to her death in 1983, in the late 1970s, Richard suffered from insomnia, panic attacks, depression, and an addiction to [[Methaqualone|Quaalude]], a sedative and hypnotic medication. Author James Gavin noted in his ''New York Times'' review of Randy L. Schmidt's biography ''Little Girl Blue: The Life of Karen Carpenter'' (2010):<ref name=\"Schmidt2010\"/> \"His mother is said to have given him his first pill,\"<ref name=\"Gavin, James\"/> an observation that was previously portrayed in the [[CBS|CBS-TV]]  television film ''[[The Karen Carpenter Story]]'' (1989) and commented on in several of that [[Television film|made-for-TV]] movie's reviews, which also noted that Agnes (their mother) had been taking them under prescription and thus thought they were safe.<ref>{{cite news|author=Weiskind, Ron|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19881231&id=RbBRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=920DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6856,8508274|title=Why: Missing From Carpenter Story|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 31, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\">{{cite news|author=Sanello, Frank|date=January 1, 1989|title=`A Puzzle For The Ages`: Film Chronicles Carpenter`s Fall But Can`t Answer Why|work=The Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-01-01/features/8902220490_1_karen-carpenter-story-mrs-carpenter-anorexia-nervosa}}</ref> At the time he sought help, Carpenter had a doctor's prescription for Quaalude as a sleep aid, but his use had gotten out of hand.\n\nA reviewer of the [[BBC]] biopic ''[[Only Yesterday: The Carpenters Story]]'' (2007) notes: \"As their fame grew, cracks began to show in their wholesome facade. An insane touring schedule began to take its toll and Richard took refuge in heroic doses of quaaludes. Meanwhile, Karen started worrying about her weight. The worrying became obsession. The cracks became faultlines. The centre could not hold.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://aerialtelly.co.uk/only-yesterday.php| work=Aerial Telly| date=April 11, 2007| author=jamdog| title=Only Yesterday \u2013 The Carpenters Story}}</ref>\n\nDr. Gabe Mirkin wrote in \"The sad story of Karen Carpenter\" (February 15, 2014), \"In those years, you could tell that something was wrong because the Carpenters frequently cancelled appearances. She appeared unhealthily thin, weighing only 90 pounds when she was 25. Richard appeared to be forgetful, and it was later found that he was addicted to Quaaludes. In 1978, the Carpenters stopped touring and in 1979 Richard went into treatment to cure his dependency on this drug.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Mirkin, Dr. Gabe|work=Village-News|url=http://www.villages-news.com/sad-story-karen-carpenter/|date=February 15, 2014|title=The sad story of Karen Carpenter}}</ref>\n\nNick Talevski similarly observes in ''Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking on Heaven's Door'' (2010): \"Constantly on the road since 1970 with their [[Las Vegas|Vegas]]-style act, both Karen and Richard Carpenter were in ill health by late 1975. With Karen's weight down to 80 pounds, a tour had to be cancelled. Richard, meanwhile, had become addicted to a prescription drug, Quaalude.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Talevski, Nick|title=Rock Obituaries \u2013 Knocking on Heaven's Door|publisher=Omnibus Press|date=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DykffzkFALoC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=richard+carpenter+has+prescription+for+quaaludes&source=bl&ots=6yrWMHwrZT&sig=oE_iljf_xrmuMFB2AapIwPz8UuI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ctECVJXOIo3NggTi_4GgAg&ved=0CFQQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=richard%20carpenter%20has%20prescription%20for%20quaaludes&f=false}}</ref>\n\nBy late 1978, Richard was receiving \"much encouragement (and browbeating) from family and friends, to \u2018face the music.\u2019\"<ref name=\"Biography\">{{cite web| url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/biography-9.htm| page=9| title=Biography| website=RichardAndKarenCarpenter.com| accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref> Finally, in January 1979, semicomatose on Quaaludes, Richard fell down a flight of stairs backstage and finally confronted his addiction.\"<ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\"/> He checked into a six-week [[Drug rehabilitation|treatment]] program<ref name=\"Biography\"/> at the [[Menninger Foundation|Menninger Clinic]] in [[Topeka, Kansas]], and kicked his habit.<ref name=\"Sanello, Frank\"/> \"For any number of reasons, the first three weeks were 'hell on earth,' Richard says, 'but after that, things really started to change, and of course, all for the better.' Still, all of this had been a monumental change for Richard and he decided it was wise not to delve right back into work, and to pretty much take the rest of 1979 off, all the better to get accustomed to his changed fortunes.\"<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n\n==Post-Carpenters==\n[[File:Carpenters - Walk of Fame.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The Carpenters' star at the Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n\nOn October 12, 1983, eight months after Karen's death, the Carpenter family celebrated the unveiling of The Carpenters' new star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. Carpenter said in his speech, \"This is a sad day, but at the same time a very special and beautiful day to my family and [me]. My only regret is that Karen is not physically here to share it with us, but I know that she is very much alive in our minds, and in our hearts.\"<ref name=cty/><ref>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|loc=[https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm/page/292 p.292]}}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 1986, Carpenter started recording the solo album ''[[Time (Richard Carpenter album)|Time]]'' and finished it on July 5, 1987.<ref>''Time,'' Richard Carpenter. \"Recording for this album commenced on June 26, 1985, with the final session in mix-down occurring on July 5, 1987.\"</ref> The album features [[Dusty Springfield]] singing \"[[Something in Your Eyes (Richard Carpenter song)|Something in Your Eyes]]\", [[Dionne Warwick]] singing \"In Love Alone\", [[Scott Grimes]] singing \"That's What I Believe\" and a song Richard created \u2013 dedicated to Karen \u2013 called \"When Time Was All We Had\", which starts off [[a cappella]], but then Richard's piano fades in as well as [[Herb Alpert]]'s [[flugelhorn]]. Lyrics include:\n\n:Our hearts were filled with music and laughter,\n:Your voice will be the sweetest sound I'll ever hear and yet,\n:We knew somehow the song would never end,\n:When time was all we had to spend.\n\nIn 1996, at the suggestion of music writer [[Daniel Levitin]], Carpenter recorded and released ''Richard Carpenter: Pianist, Arranger, Composer, Conductor'', which included reworkings of many Carpenters favorites, including hits and album tracks, and ends with \"Karen's Theme\", which Carpenter composed for the television film, ''The Karen Carpenter Story'' (1989).\n\nCarpenter released the DVDs ''[[Gold: Greatest Hits (video)|Gold: Greatest Hits]]'' (2002), a repackaging of the [[VHS]]/[[Betamax]] ''Yesterday Once More'' (released in 1985, two years after Karen's death in 1983) that contains all the videos from ''Yesterday Once More'', and ''[[Interpretations (The Carpenters DVD)|Interpretations]]'' (2003), which updates the original, VHS/cassette tape released in 1995 and includes footage from the Carpenters' five TV specials and TV series from 1971\u20131980. The DVD follows the compilation album of the same name, which had been released earlier the same year, and includes eleven Carpenters' tracks never before available on DVD (including \"From This Moment On\", an outtake from the Carpenters' fifth television special), all of them digitally enhanced and remastered in stereo audio.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=A&M|authors=Carpenter, Richard & Carpenter, Karen|date= July 29, 2003|asin= B0000A9D2F|url=https://www.amazon.com/Carpenters-Interpretations/dp/B0000A9D2F/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1409460224&sr=8-2&keywords=interpretations%2Cthe+carpenters|title=Capenters \u2013 Interpretations}}</ref>\n\nOn his 62nd birthday in October 2008, at a luncheon for The Foreign Correspondents Club of Japan, Carpenter announced plans for \"his career comeback \u2013 dubbed 'Richard Carpenter Strikes Back'\"\u2014which included \"the re-release of a Carpenters Christmas album and a tribute album featuring cover versions of Carpenters songs.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Carpenter ready to make a comeback |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/richard-carpenter-ready-to-make-a-comeback-1.334069 |website=CTV News |publisher=Associated Press |language=en |date=October 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=October 2008| website=Smooth Radio| title=Take a Look At Carpenters In Pictures: Richard Carpenter \u2013 a comeback?| url =http://www.smoothradio.com/artists/carpenters/carpenters-pictures/richard-carpenter-a-comeback/| author=AP Photo}}</ref>\n\n===Documentaries===\nThe 43-minute film ''[[Superstar: The Karen Carpenter Story]]'' (1987) was directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and was withdrawn from circulation in 1990, after Haynes lost a [[copyright infringement]] lawsuit filed by Richard.<ref name=\"holden\">{{cite news|author=[[Holden]], Stephen |date=November 8, 1998|title=FILM; Focusing on Glam Rock's Blurring of Identity|work=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> The film's title is derived from [[The Carpenters]]' 1971 hit song, \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)#Carpenters version|Superstar]].\"  Over the years, it has developed into a [[cult film]] and is included in ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s 2003 list of top 50 cult movies.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dirks, Tim|url=http://www.filmsite.org/cultfilmsew2.html|title=Top 50 Cult Movies|work= [[Entertainment Weekly]]/[[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]|accessdate= January 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCarpenter helped in the productions of the documentaries ''[[Close to You: Remembering the Carpenters]]'' (1997) and ''[[Only Yesterday: The Carpenters Story]]'' (2007).\n\n===Scholarship/talent show===\nCarpenter funds an annual scholarship/talent show for people with artistic abilities that is held at the Thousand Oaks Civic Center.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n===Gear===\nCarpenter used a wide range of keyboard instruments including [[grand piano]], [[Hammond organ]], [[Wurlitzer electric piano]], [[ARP Odyssey]], [[Rhodes piano|Fender Rhodes electric piano]], [[harpsichord]], [[celesta]], [[synthesizer]] and [[tack piano]]. His favourite grand piano was [[Baldwin Piano Company|Baldwin]]. In the '70s, he initially endorsed and used Wurlitzer electric pianos before switching to the [[Rhodes piano|Fender Rhodes electric piano]]. He says that at [[A&M Studios]], he regularly used a [[Steinway]] piano on the Carpenters' records with the exception of the ''[[A Song for You (The Carpenters album)|A Song for You]]'' album in which he played a Baldwin piano which was autographed by Liberace. On stage, he had both a Wurlitzer electric piano and grand piano, but after switching to the Fender Rhodes, he would simply alternate between the three for different songs on stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/fans_ask_Archive-All.htm|title=Carpenters Fans Ask-Richard Answers Archive|website=www.richardandkarencarpenter.com}}</ref> He has described the sound of the Wurlitzer electric piano as \"warm\" and \"beautiful\" and via [[overdubbing]] in the studio, he would regularly supplement his grand piano with a Wurlitzer electric piano to thicken the sound, thus creating a distinctive keyboard sound. On the song \"Happy\" on ''[[Horizon (The Carpenters album)|Horizon]],'' he made his earliest experiments with the [[ARP Odyssey]] synthesizer.<ref>John Tobler. ''The Complete Guide to the Music of the Carpenters'' (1997); Omnibus Press, London; {{ISBN|0-7119-6312-6}};  p.67</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2014}}\nIn 1984, Carpenter married his adopted cousin, Mary Rudolph.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoerburger|first1=Rob|title=Karen Carpenter's Second Life|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/06/magazine/karen-carpenter-s-second-life.html?pagewanted=3|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=4 August 2015|quote=[I]n 1984, the year after Karen died, he married his cousin Mary Rudolph and is now the father of four.}}</ref> Her brother, Mark Rudolph, was the Carpenters' [[road manager]] as well as the radio call-in \"contestant\" in the [Oldies] \"Medley\" on the album ''[[Now & Then (The Carpenters album)|Now & Then]]'' (1973). The couple had been dating since the late 1970s. A young Mary made a cameo appearance in the Carpenters' promotional video for the song \"[[I Need to Be in Love]]\" (1976).\n\nRichard and Mary Carpenter have five children: Kristi Lynn (the name Karen would have given to a daughter) was born on August 17, 1987; Traci Tatum on July 25, 1989; Mindi Karen (named after her late paternal aunt) on July 7, 1992; Collin Paul on July 20, 1994; and Taylor Mary on December 5, 2000.<ref name=pp297>{{harvnb|Schmidt|2010|loc=[https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm/page/297 pp.297\u2013298]}}</ref> Today the family resides in [[Thousand Oaks, California]], and Richard and the children sometimes perform music together at various Carpenter-related events.<ref name=pp297/>\n\nCarpenter is a [[Mopar]] automobile enthusiast, and original owner of a 1970 [[Plymouth Barracuda]] with the unusual 440+6 V8 engine and automatic transmission package.<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Carpenter's 1970 Chrysler Barracuda|url=http://www.nbc.com/jay-lenos-garage/video/richard-carpenters-1970-chrysler-barracuda/310108|website=Jay Leno's Garage|accessdate=21 September 2016|date=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n=== The Carpenters ===\n{{Main|The Carpenters discography|List of songs recorded by The Carpenters}}\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"33\"| Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1987\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Time (Richard Carpenter album)|Time]]'''''\n| \n* Released in October 1987\n* Richard Carpenter's debut solo album\n* Included guest singers [[Dusty Springfield]], [[Dionne Warwick]], and actor [[Scott Grimes]]\n* Out of print\n* Label: [[A&M Records]]\n* Formats: [[LP album]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette tape]], [[Compact Disc|compact disc]], digital download\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|align=\"left\"|'''''[[Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 Composer \u2022 Conductor|Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 <br>Composer \u2022 Conductor]]'''''\n| \n* Released on January 27, 1998\n* Richard's second and latest solo album\n* Includes instrumentals of popular songs of Carpenters\n* Dedicated to Richard's deceased mother, Agnes Carpenter<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web |url= http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/|title= Richard and Karen Carpenter \u2013 Official website|accessdate=2008-01-17 |author= Carpenter, Richard}}</ref>\n* Label: A&M Records\n* Formats: Cassette tape (out of print), compact disc (out of print), digital download\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Song\n!colspan=\"6\"|Chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\"|B-side\n!rowspan=\"2\"|<sup>[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]<br>cert.</sup><ref name=\"riaas\">{{cite web |url= https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Carpenters&format=SINGLE&go=Search&perPage=50|title=RIAA Gold and Platinum Search for singles by the Carpenters|accessdate=2008-07-03}}</ref>\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n|-\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. Hot 100]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Adult Contemporary (chart)|U.S. AC]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Canadian Singles Chart|CAN]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[Oricon Singles Chart|JPN]]</sup>\n!width=\"35\"|<sup>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</sup>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1987\n|\"[[Something in Your Eyes (Richard Carpenter song)|Something in Your Eyes]]\"<br><small>''(featuring [[Dusty Springfield]])''</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|84\n|<small>\"Time\"</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''Time''\n|-\n|\"Calling Your Name Again\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\"When Time Was All We Had\"</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1998\n|\"Karen's Theme\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\u2014</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''Pianist \u2022 Arranger \u2022 Composer \u2022 Conductor''\n|-\n|\"Medley\"\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|<small>\u2014</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Randy|title=Little Girl Blue: The Life Of Karen Carpenter|year=2010|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-1-556-52976-4|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/littlegirlblueli00schm}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.richardandkarencarpenter.com/ Richard and Karen Carpenter Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|0139443|name=Richard Carpenter}}\n*[http://www.myokom.info/ Make Your Own Kind of Music] \u2013 1971 Summer Television Series\n\n{{The Carpenters albums}}\n\n{{Portal| Biography }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carpenter, Richard}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New Haven, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:A&M Records artists]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American pop pianists]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American Methodists]]\n[[Category:American soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Downey, California]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:The Carpenters members]]\n[[Category:California State University, Long Beach alumni]]\n[[Category:American jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:American male pianists]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:American pop keyboardists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n", "name_user": "Tabledhote", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePost-Carpenters:punctuation plethora prevention", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Carpenter_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Fieracavalli", "text_new": "{{Infobox Convention\n|image         = \n|begins        = \n|ends          =\n|date          = Annually\n|location      = Verona Exhibition Centre, [[Verona]], [[Italy]] \n|first         = 1898\n|last          = 7 November 2013 \u2013 10  November 2013\n|next          = 6 November 2014 \u2013 9 November 2014\n|attendance    = 158,000 by 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Fieracavalli 2013 Facts & Figures|url=http://www.fieracavalli.it/en/fieracavalli-2013-facts-figures|website=Fieracavalli |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Fieracavalli''' is an international show dedicated to horses and horse riding, which takes place in [[Verona]] every year from 1898<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fieracavalli, oggi si parte: \u00e8 subito festa |url=http://corrieredelveneto.corriere.it/veneto/notizie/cronaca/2014/6-novembre-2014/fieracavalli-oggi-si-parte-subito-festa-230484496011.shtml |newspaper=Corriere del Veneto |publisher=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=7 November 2014 |accessdate=9 November 2014 }}</ref> in early November.\nSince 2001 the Festival hosts the only Italian stage Rolex FEI World Cup, International Grand Prix jump obstacles. The Italian stage Jumping Verona is held inside the Exhibition Centre during the event.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Potter|first1=Leslie|title=Video: Fieracavalli in Three Minutes|url=http://www.horsechannel.com/horse-community/fieracavalli-in-three-minutes.aspx|website=HorseChannel.com|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.fieracavalli.it/en/ Official website]\n*https://exposale.net/en/exhibition/fieracavalli\n\n[[Category:Fairs in Italy]]\n[[Category:Annual fairs]]\n[[Category:Autumn events in Italy]]\n\n\n{{horse-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Convention\n|image         = \n|begins        = \n|ends          =\n|date          = Annually\n|location      = Verona Exhibition Centre, [[Verona]], [[Italy]] \n|first         = 1898\n|last          = 7 November 2013 \u2013 10  November 2013\n|next          = 6 November 2014 \u2013 9 November 2014\n|attendance    = 158,000 by 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Fieracavalli 2013 Facts & Figures|url=http://www.fieracavalli.it/en/fieracavalli-2013-facts-figures|website=Fieracavalli |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Fieracavalli''' is an international show dedicated to horses and horse riding, which takes place in [[Verona]] every year from 1898<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Fieracavalli, oggi si parte: \u00e8 subito festa |url=http://corrieredelveneto.corriere.it/veneto/notizie/cronaca/2014/6-novembre-2014/fieracavalli-oggi-si-parte-subito-festa-230484496011.shtml |newspaper=Corriere del Veneto |publisher=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=7 November 2014 |accessdate=9 November 2014 }}</ref> in early November.\nSince 2001 the Festival hosts the only Italian stage Rolex FEI World Cup, International Grand Prix jump obstacles. The Italian stage Jumping Verona is held inside the Exhibition Centre during the event.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Potter|first1=Leslie|title=Video: Fieracavalli in Three Minutes|url=http://www.horsechannel.com/horse-community/fieracavalli-in-three-minutes.aspx|website=HorseChannel.com|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.fieracavalli.it/en/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Fairs in Italy]]\n[[Category:Annual fairs]]\n[[Category:Autumn events in Italy]]\n\n\n{{horse-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lusine325", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fieracavalli"}
{"title_page": "Vistara", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian airline}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline = Vistara\n| image = \n| logo = Vistara logo.svg\n| logo_size = 180\n| fleet_size = 40\n| destinations = 34\n| IATA = UK\n| ICAO = VTI\n| callsign = VISTARA\n| parent = \n<div>\n* [[Tata Sons]] (51%)\n* [[Singapore Airlines]] (49%)\n</div>\n| company_slogan = ''Fly the new feeling''\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2013}}\n| commenced = {{Start date|df=yes|2015|01|09}}\n| headquarters = Level 10, [[One Horizon Center]], Golf Course Rd, [[Gurgaon]]\n| key_people = {{ubl|Bhaskar Bhat ([[chairman]])|Leslie Thng ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| aoc = \n| hubs = {{nowrap|[[Indira Gandhi International Airport]]}}\n| secondary_hubs = \n| focus_cities = \n| frequent_flyer = Club Vistara\n| alliance = \n| num_employees = 900 (March 2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-way-to-fly|title=New way to fly: Vistara chief shakes up India's domestic travel|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=26 March 2016|access-date=26 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403095818/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-way-to-fly|archivedate=3 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.airvistara.com/|airvistara.com}}\n}}\n'''Tata SIA Airlines Limited''', operating as '''Vistara''', is an Indian  full-service [[airline]], based in [[Gurgaon]], with its hub at [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]]. The carrier, a joint venture between [[Tata Sons]] and [[Singapore Airlines]], commenced operations on 9 January 2015 with its inaugural flight between [[Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]]. The airline had carried more than two million passengers by June 2016<ref name=\"UK2million\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/vistara-looking-strategic-partnerships-expand-business-683235|title=Vistara looking at strategic partnerships to expand business|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=17 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618150139/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/vistara-looking-strategic-partnerships-expand-business-683235|archivedate=18 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and as of May 2019, has a 4.7% share <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/india-s-domestic-air-traffic-grows-3-in-may-after-registering-a-fall-in-april-1560858888397.html|title=India\u2019s domestic air traffic grows 3% in May after registering a fall in April|last=Kundu|first=Rhik|date=2019-06-18|website=Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> of the domestic carrier market, making it the 6th largest domestic airline.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dgca.nic.in/reports/Traffic_reports/Traffic_Rep052017.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-07-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729172913/http://dgca.nic.in/reports/Traffic_reports/Traffic_Rep052017.pdf |archivedate=29 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The airline serves 34<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/destinations|title=Vistara/ Our Destinations|work=Vistara |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> destinations with a fleet of [[Airbus A320]], [[Boeing 787]] and [[Boeing 737 800|Boeing 737-800NG]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/airvistara/status/1134447502919372801|title=We are delighted to announce that our first commercial Boeing 737-800NG flight will fly this evening, Delhi-Amritsar-Delhi, UK695/694. Here's to loads more in the coming days and weeks! #FlyTheNewFeelingpic.twitter.com/G6qwSINFk9|last=Vistara|date=2019-05-31|website=@airvistara|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> aircraft.\n<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/auto/vistara-boeing-787-9-dreamliner-2541295.html</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Vistara Airbus A320-232 at Delhi Airport.jpg|thumb|right|Vistara's first Airbus A320 aircraft (VT-TTB)<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/31512-indias-vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft | title=India's Vistara takes delivery of first aircraft | work=[[ch-aviation]] | date=30 September 2014 | accessdate=30 July 2016 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817025842/http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/31512-indias-vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft | archivedate=17 August 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at Delhi IGI Airport]]\n\nThe airline was founded in 2013 as a [[joint venture]] (JV) between India's conglomerate Tata Sons and Singapore Airlines (SIA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/VDL#al_profile_tab_info|title=Airline Information: Air Vistara (Ch-aviation)|publisher=[[Ch-aviation]]|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923185845/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/VDL#al_profile_tab_info|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"launch\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Tata-Sons-Singapore-Airlines-Vistara-set-for-October-launch/articleshow/40063616.cms|title=Tata Sons-Singapore Airlines 'Vistara' set for October launch|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=11 August 2014|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Tata-Sons-Singapore-Airlines-Vistara-set-for-October-launch/articleshow/40063616.cms|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-takes-to-the-skies-operates-first-flight-from-delhi-to-mumbai/articleshow/45823316.cms|title=Vistara takes to the skies, operates first flight from Delhi to Mumbai|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=9 January 2015|access-date=24 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827212527/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-takes-to-the-skies-operates-first-flight-from-delhi-to-mumbai/articleshow/45823316.cms|archivedate=27 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-carries-one-million-passengers/article8021439.ece|title=Vistara carries one million passengers|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=23 December 2015|access-date=23 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303131917/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-carries-one-million-passengers/article8021439.ece|archivedate=3 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/press_release_news/ne130919.jsp|title=Tata, Singapore Airlines look to fly in Indian skies|work=[[Singapore Airlines]]|date=19 September 2013|access-date=12 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171407/http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/press_release_news/ne130919.jsp|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two companies had made a bid in the mid-1990s to launch a full service carrier in India that was unsuccessful, being denied regulatory approval by the Indian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/two-decades-in-the-departure-lounge-115010800788_1.html|title=Two decades in the departure lounge|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=9 January 2015|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035600/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/two-decades-in-the-departure-lounge-115010800788_1.html|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With India opening up its airline sector for 49 percent [[foreign direct investment]] (FDI) in 2012, Tata and SIA once again decided to float a JV airline company in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/singapore-airlines-tata-joint-venture-proposal-would-be-a-big-boost-for-sia---and-airasia-129471|title=Singapore Airlines-Tata joint venture proposal would be a big boost for SIA \u2013 and AirAsia?|publisher=CAPA|date=20 September 2013|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/singapore-airlines-tata-joint-venture-proposal-would-be-a-big-boost-for-sia---and-airasia-129471|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The JV, Tata SIA Airlines Limited (TSAL), was envisaged as a premium full-service carrier to cater to the demands of [[high-end]] business travellers in India's civil aviation market dominated by [[low-cost carrier]]s. India's [[Foreign Investment Promotion Board]] approved the JV in October 2013, allowing SIA to take a 49 percent stake in the airline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-tata-proposal-gets-green-light-indias-foreign-investment-board-201|title=SIA, Tata proposal gets green light from India's foreign investment board|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=24 October 2013|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022135529/http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-tata-proposal-gets-green-light-indias-foreign-investment-board-201|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two parent companies initially pledged to invest a combined {{US$|100mn|link=yes}} as start-up capital, with Tata Sons owning 51 percent and Singapore Airlines owning the remaining 49 percent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-partners-tata-group-set-new-airline-india-20130919|title=SIA partners Tata group to set up new airline in India|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=19 September 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022134011/http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-partners-tata-group-set-new-airline-india-20130919|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was part of Tata's second major foray into the aviation sector along with a minority stake in [[AirAsia India]].<ref name=\"reborn\">{{cite news|title=With Vistara, a Tata airline is reborn|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/with-vistara-a-tata-airline-is-reborn-115010800126_1.html|first=Aneesh|last=Phadnis|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|location=Mumbai|date=9 January 2015|access-date=13 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607131134/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/with-vistara-a-tata-airline-is-reborn-115010800126_1.html|archivedate=7 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company's first venture, Tata Airlines, was established in the 1930s and later became the flag carrier [[Air India]] after nationalization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/todays-newspaper/tata-forays-into-sky-with-vistara.html|title=Tata forays into the skies with Vistara|newspaper=[[The Pioneer (newspaper)|The Pioneer]]|date=12 August 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923232359/http://www.dailypioneer.com/todays-newspaper/tata-forays-into-sky-with-vistara.html|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe company unveiled its brand identity \"Vistara\" on 11 August 2014.<ref name=\"launch\"/> The name was taken from the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vist\u0101ra'', meaning \"limitless expanse\".<ref name=\"vistara\">{{cite press release|title=Tata SIA christens its airline, Vistara|url=http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/Tata-SIA-christens-its-airline-Vistara|work=[[Tata Sons]]|date=14 August 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113222042/http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/Tata-SIA-christens-its-airline-Vistara|archivedate=13 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"vistarameaning\">{{cite web|title=Vistara meaning|url=http://www.spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=HK&beginning=0+&tinput=+vistara&trans=Translate&direction=AU|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224063529/http://www.spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=HK&beginning=0+&tinput=+vistara&trans=Translate&direction=AU|archivedate=24 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara received its [[air operator's certificate]] from the [[Directorate General of Civil Aviation (India)|Directorate General of Civil Aviation]] on 15 December 2014 and started operations on 9 January 2015.<ref name=\"reborn\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-set-to-take-off-in-jan-gets-air-operator-permit-114121500939_1.html|title=Vistara gets air operator permit, to take off in Jan|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=16 December 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216131327/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-set-to-take-off-in-jan-gets-air-operator-permit-114121500939_1.html|archivedate=16 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-12-15/news/57072156_1_vistara-phee-teik-yeoh-full-service-airline|title=Tata-Singapore Airlines joint venture airline Vistara gets flying permit, to announce schedule soon|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 December 2014|access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> Vistara became the first carrier to operate domestic services out of the new Terminal 2 at Mumbai's [[Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-operate-out-of-mumbai-international-airports-new-t2-terminal/articleshow/45712273.cms|title=Vistara to operate out of Mumbai International Airport\u2019s new T2 terminal|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=1 January 2015|access-date=2 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827224102/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-operate-out-of-mumbai-international-airports-new-t2-terminal/articleshow/45712273.cms|archivedate=27 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 24 August 2015, Vistara inaugurated the Aviation Security Training Institute, an in-house institute for training its cockpit and cabin crew, security staff and others related to aviation industry. The institute has secured the necessary approvals from the nodal body [[Bureau of Civil Aviation Security]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-08-24/news/65808454_1_vistara-joint-venture-carrier-aviation-security-training-institute|title=Tata-SIA joint venture carrier Vistara sets up security training institute|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=24 August 2015|access-date=30 August 2015}}</ref> From the first month of operation, Vistara consistently achieved very high [[on-time performance]] records of over 90 percent, the highest among India's domestic carriers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/interview-we-are-still-a-crawling-infant-wait-for-us-to-get-up-and-run-says-vistara-2116201|title=We are still a crawling infant, wait for us to get up and run, says Vistara|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=20 August 2015|access-date=20 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820213044/http://www.dnaindia.com/money/interview-we-are-still-a-crawling-infant-wait-for-us-to-get-up-and-run-says-vistara-2116201|archivedate=20 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistaras-otp-stands-at-89-per-cent-in-1st-month-of-operation/article6933544.ece|title=Vistara\u2019s OTP stands at 89 percent in 1st month of operation|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=25 February 2015|access-date=2 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194945/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistaras-otp-stands-at-89-per-cent-in-1st-month-of-operation/article6933544.ece|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 20 August 2015, Vistara declared it had carried half a million passengers in just over seven months of operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://centreforaviation.com/news/vistara-reaches-500000-pax-milestone-475569|title=Vistara reaches 500,000 pax milestone|work=CAPA|date=21 August 2015|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://centreforaviation.com/news/vistara-reaches-500000-pax-milestone-475569|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of February 2016, Vistara has a share of 2% in the domestic carrier market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-domestic-passenger-demand-up-25-percent-iata-116040700595_1.html|title=India's domestic passenger demand up 25 percent: IATA|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=6 April 2014|access-date=14 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423143800/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-domestic-passenger-demand-up-25-percent-iata-116040700595_1.html|archivedate=23 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara recently received the membership of the International Air Transport Association (IATA),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-joins-global-airlines-body-iata-ahead-of-international-operations/article23710253.ece|title=Vistara joins global airlines\u2019 body IATA ahead of international operations|work=@businessline|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref> joining the association of more than 280 airlines around the world that represents, leads and serves the airline industry. With this, Vistara becomes one of the select few airlines in India to have the IATA membership.\n\nVistara announced on 11 July 2019 that their first international destination would be Singapore. The airline started its first international service from Delhi to Singapore and Mumbai to Singapore on 6 and 7 August respectively using the [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800 NG]] which was earlier used by [[Jet Airways]].<ref>{{cite news |title=India's Vistara to launch international flights, starting with Singapore in August |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/vistara-new-singapore-india-flight-date-delhi-mumbai-11711134 |accessdate=11 July 2019 |work=CNA |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chowdhury |first1=Anirban |title=Vistara to launch international operations to Singapore from August |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-launch-international-operations-to-singapore-from-august/articleshow/70163712.cms |accessdate=11 July 2019 |work=The Economic Times |date=10 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/vistara-makes-international-debut-on-an-aircraft-used-by-jet-airways-4300881.html|title=Vistara makes international debut, on an aircraft used by Jet Airways|work=Moneycontrol.com|date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February 2020, the airline took the delivery of its first wide-body [[Boeing 787-9]], becoming the first Indian airline to operate this aircraft and yet to receive five more such aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vistara takes delivery of India's first Dreamliner plane with lie-flat business class seats |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/vistara-delivery-india-first-dreamliner-plane-lie-flat-business-class-seats-1650728-2020-02-28 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=India Today |agency=Press Trust of India |date=28 February 2020 |location=Washington |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate affairs==\nOn 15 April 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://site2corp.com/in/phee-teik-yeoh-2/companies|title=Phee Teik Yeoh \u2013 Director / Owner Information|website=site2corp.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001162751/http://site2corp.com/in/phee-teik-yeoh-2/companies|archivedate=1 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara chose Mr Phee Teik Yeoh as the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) and Mr Giam Ming Toh<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketnewsalert.com/2015/04/Mr-Giam-Ming-Toh-is-the-Chief-Commercial-Officer-of-Vistara.html|title=Mr Giam Ming Toh is the Chief Commercial Officer of Vistara|website=www.pocketnewsalert.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001165816/http://www.pocketnewsalert.com/2015/04/Mr-Giam-Ming-Toh-is-the-Chief-Commercial-Officer-of-Vistara.html|archivedate=1 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as the [[chief commercial officer]] (CCO), both from Singapore Airlines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/ready-to-fly-vistara-poaches-key-men-from-indigo-jetlite/article1-1261191.aspx|title=Vistara poaches key men from IndiGo, JetLite|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=8 September 2014|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104203613/http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/ready-to-fly-vistara-poaches-key-men-from-indigo-jetlite/article1-1261191.aspx|archivedate=4 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Vistara shifted to its new office at the [[One Horizon Center]] tower in Sector 43, [[Gurgaon]], a [[satellite city]] of Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/few-takers-for-office-space-in-metro-cities/46642/|title=Few takers for office space in metro cities|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|date=24 February 2015|access-date=8 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415065335/http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/few-takers-for-office-space-in-metro-cities/46642/|archivedate=15 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/vistara-chases-small-aviation-market-with-big-ambitions/1/217140.html|title=Battle of Class|newspaper=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]]|date=April 2015|access-date=8 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403180651/http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/vistara-chases-small-aviation-market-with-big-ambitions/1/217140.html|archivedate=3 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Initially it started out with a three-member board comprising Swee Wah Mak (SIA group), Mukund Rajan and Prasad Menon (Tata group), with the latter as chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistara-spreads-wings-to-add-goa-hyderabad-flights-by-march/article6815635.ece|title=Vistara spreads wings; to add Goa, Hyderabad flights by March|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=23 January 2015|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194945/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistara-spreads-wings-to-add-goa-hyderabad-flights-by-march/article6815635.ece|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/people-first-vistaras-top-executives-spending-time-with-employees-on-the-ground-tackling-issues/articleshow/48565166.cms|title='People first': Vistara's top executives spending time with employees on the ground & tackling issues|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=21 August 2015|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825050954/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/people-first-vistaras-top-executives-spending-time-with-employees-on-the-ground-tackling-issues/articleshow/48565166.cms|archivedate=25 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In August 2015, the airline expanded the board by introducing two new members, Som Mittal and Sangeeta Pendurkar, along with an equity infusion of {{INRconvert|2|b}}, part of {{INRconvert|5|b}} initially planned by Tata and SIA together.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/tata-sia-infuse-rs-500-crore-in-vistara-115090600209_1.html|title=Tata Sons, SIA infuse Rs 500 cr in Vistara|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=6 September 2015|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907210800/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/tata-sia-infuse-rs-500-crore-in-vistara-115090600209_1.html|archivedate=7 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/40091-tata-group-singapore-airlines-boost-vistaras-coffers|title=Tata Group, Singapore Airlines boost Vistara's coffers|work=[[Ch-aviation]]|date=8 September 2015|access-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910151101/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/40091-tata-group-singapore-airlines-boost-vistaras-coffers|archivedate=10 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2016, Bhaskar Bhat, present Managing Director of [[Titan Company|Titan]], joined as the new chairman following Prasad Menon's retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.titan.co.in/control//Corporate/Board-of-Directors|title=Titan Company Board of Directors|work=[[Titan Company|Titan]]|date=18 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117110607/http://www.titan.co.in/control/Corporate/Board-of-Directors|archivedate=17 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/ZRdG7GYaYyW1cSd0uYRvjO/Bhaskar-Bhat-named-Vistara-chairman.html|title=Bhaskar Bhat named Vistara chairman|newspaper=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=14 January 2016|access-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117191207/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/ZRdG7GYaYyW1cSd0uYRvjO/Bhaskar-Bhat-named-Vistara-chairman.html|archivedate=17 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bhaskar-bhat-joins-vistara-as-chairman-116011400857_1.html|title=Bhaskar Bhat joins Vistara as chairman|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=14 January 2016|access-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302140304/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bhaskar-bhat-joins-vistara-as-chairman-116011400857_1.html|archivedate=2 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2016, Vistara appointed Sanjiv Kapoor as its chief strategy and commercial officer as the successor to Giam Ming Toh who was scheduled to leave in mid April 2016 following completion of his deputation at Vistara.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/former-spicejet-coo-sanjiv-kapoor-joins-vistara-as-commercial-and-strategy-chief/articleshow/51205907.cms|title=Former SpiceJet COO Sanjiv Kapoor joins Vistara as commercial and strategy chief|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403002936/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/former-spicejet-coo-sanjiv-kapoor-joins-vistara-as-commercial-and-strategy-chief/articleshow/51205907.cms|archivedate=3 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 October 2017, it was announced that Leslie Thng would succeed Yeoh Phee Teik as CEO of Vistara.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/leslie-thng-vistara-chief-executive-officer|title=Leslie Thng joins Vistara as chief executive officer via @tatacompanies|work=tata.com|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201193009/http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/leslie-thng-vistara-chief-executive-officer|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mr Yeoh returned to Singapore  Airlines to take up a senior management role as Acting Senior Vice President of Customer Experience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/vistara-ceo-phee-teik-yeoh-likely-to-join-sia/articleshow/61060156.cms|title=Vistara CEO Phee Teik Yeoh likely to join SIA as product & customer service head|last=Mishra|first=Mihir|date=2017-10-13|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-02-01|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201192954/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/vistara-ceo-phee-teik-yeoh-likely-to-join-sia/articleshow/61060156.cms|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mr Thng was serving as Chief Commercial Officer of Budget Aviation Holdings, a Singapore Airlines subsidiary, prior to his appointment in Vistara.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/top-level-shuffles-in-the-sia-group/|title=Top level shuffle in the SIA group|last=Manjur|first=Rezwana|work=Marketing Interactive|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201193005/http://www.marketing-interactive.com/top-level-shuffles-in-the-sia-group/|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before that, Mr Thng was the Chief Executive Officer of SilkAir, a full service regional airline under Singapore Airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://centreforaviation.com/news/silkair-names-new-ceo-168199|title=SilkAir names new CEO |website=centreforaviation.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\n{{Main|List of Vistara destinations}}\nAs of October 2019, Vistara serves 24 destinations with over 1200 flights a week.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/company-info|title=About Vistara \u2013 Tata Singapore Airlines Joint Venture|website=www.airvistara.com}}</ref>   Its only hub is at the [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]] from where it operates all of its flights. Vistara's first flight was on 9 January 2015, from Delhi to Mumbai.<ref name=\"auto\"/> On 6 August 2019, the airline launched its first international flight from Delhi to Singapore using a [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800NG]] aircraft which was earlier used by [[Jet Airways]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/vistara-makes-international-debut-on-an-aircraft-used-by-jet-airways-4300881.html|title=Vistara makes international debut, on an aircraft used by Jet Airways|work=Moneycontrol.com|date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Codeshare agreements===\nVistara [[codeshare agreement|codeshares]] with the following airlines:\n*[[British Airways]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massy-Beresford |first1=Helen |title=British Airways to codeshare with Indian domestic carrier Vistara |url=http://atwonline.com/airlines/british-airways-codeshare-indian-domestic-carrier-vistara |publisher=[[Air Transport World]] |date=6 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914161536/http://atwonline.com/airlines/british-airways-codeshare-indian-domestic-carrier-vistara |archivedate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n* [[SilkAir]]<ref name=\"Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.singaporeair.com/en_UK/us/media-centre/press-release/article/?q=en_UK/2017/January-March/jr0617-170314|title=Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights|website=www.singaporeair.com}}</ref>\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]<ref name=\"Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights\" />\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[United Airlines]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.united.com/2019-06-18-united-airlines-and-vistara-establish-codeshare-agreement-2638904487.html|title=United Airlines and Vistara Establish Codeshare Agreement|date=2019-06-18|website=United Hub|language=en|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n* [[Deutsche Lufthansa|Lufthansa]]<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/vistara-signs-codeshare-agreement-with-lufthansa/articleshow/72438123.cms</ref>\n\n===Interline agreements===\nVistara has [[interline agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=VistaraInterline>{{cite web|url=https://airvistara.com/trip/interline-partners|title=Vistara Interline Patners|publisher=Vistara|accessdate=6 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103193600/https://airvistara.com/trip/interline-partners |archive-date=2016-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Aeroflot]]\n* [[Air France]]\n* [[Air Mauritius]] \n* [[All Nippon Airways]]\n* [[Asiana Airlines]]\n* [[British Airways]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/british-airways-may-expand-its-interline-agreement-with-vistara/articleshow/49541297.cms|title=British Airways may expand its interline agreement with Vistara \u2013 The Economic Times|website=The Economic Times|access-date=2016-06-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170150/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/british-airways-may-expand-its-interline-agreement-with-vistara/articleshow/49541297.cms|archivedate=21 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] \n* [[Ethiopian Airlines]]\n* [[Finnair]]\n* [[flydubai]]\n* [[Gulf Air]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Kenya Airways]]\n* [[KLM]]\n* [[Kuwait Airways]]\n* [[Qatar Airways]]<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2017/Aug/qatar-airways_-new-interline-partnership-takes-off-with-vistara.html# |title=Qatar Airways\u2019 New Interline Partnership Takes Off With Vistara |publisher=Qatar Airways |date=22 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825111835/https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2017/Aug/qatar-airways_-new-interline-partnership-takes-off-with-vistara.html|archivedate=25 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[SilkAir]]\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]<ref name=codeshare>{{cite news|first=P.R.|last=Sanjai|title=Vistara signs inter-line agreement with Singapore Airlines, SilkAir|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/VrpAhLBg97M3RffJN9pm2M/Vistara-signs-interline-agreement-with-Singapore-Air-Silk.html|newspaper=[[Live Mint]]|access-date=2 January 2015|date=22 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102131039/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/VrpAhLBg97M3RffJN9pm2M/Vistara-signs-interline-agreement-with-Singapore-Air-Silk.html|archivedate=2 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Sri Lankan Airlines]]\n* [[Turkish Airlines]]\n* [[United Airlines]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Fleet==\n[[File:Vistara_VT-TTF_at_Bengaluru,_2016-02-20.jpg|thumb|Vistara [[Airbus A320-200]]]]\n[[File:Vistara VT-TSD Dreamliner.jpg|thumb|VT-TSD, the first [[Boeing 787-9]] in the airline's fleet.]]\n{{As of|2019|12}}, the Vistara fleet consists of the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite journal |title=Global Airline Guide 2019 (Part One) |journal=Airliner World |issue=October 2019 |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dron|first1=Alan|title=India\u2019s Vistara prepares for international services|url=http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/india-s-vistara-prepares-international-services|publisher=[[Air Transport World]]|date=6 April 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418080754/http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/india-s-vistara-prepares-international-services|archivedate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Airbus_Orders\">{{cite web|url= https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o&d/ODs-November-2019-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft.xlsx|title= Airbus orders and deliveries|publisher= Airbus|date= November 2019|archive-date= 7 December 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191207004822/https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o&d/ODs-November-2019-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft.xlsx|access-date= 7 December 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Vistara fleet\n|- \n|- style=\"background:#662046;\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Aircraft</span>\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">In service</span>\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Orders</span>\n!colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Passenger</span>\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Notes</span>\n|- style=\"background:#662046;\"\n! style=\"background:#662046;\" |<abbr title=\"Business Class\"><span style=\"color:white;\">J</span></abbr>\n! style=\"background:#662046;\" |<abbr title=\"Premium Economy Class\"><span style=\"color:white;\">S</span></abbr>\n! style=\"background:#662046;\" |<abbr title=\"Economy Class\"><span style=\"color:white;\">Y</span></abbr>\n! style=\"background:#662046;\" |<span style=\"color:white;\">Total</span>\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320-200]]\n|13\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|24 \n|126\n|158\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320neo family|Airbus A320neo]]\n|19<ref name=\"Vistara A320N\">{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-order-26-cfm-engines-worth-2-4-billion/articleshow/71634739.cms?from=mdr|title=Vistara to order 26 CFM engines worth $2.4 billion|work=Economic Times|date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n|41<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/85204-indias-vistara-explores-options-to-gain-london-slots|title=India's Vistara explores options to gain London slots|website=ch-aviation.com|date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n|8\n|24\n|126\n|158\n|One aircraft is Full Economy Cabin Configuration\n|-\n|{{nowrap|[[A321neo|Airbus A321neo]]}}\n|&mdash;\n|6<ref name=\"A321neo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/73268-indias-vistara-to-add-maiden-a321neo-in-2020|title=India's Vistara to add maiden A321neo in 2020|work=ch-aviation|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en}}</ref>\n| colspan=\"4\" |TBA \n|\n|-\n|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]]\n|7<ref>https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/01/15/vistara-phases-out-boeing-737-aircraft/</ref>\n| \u2014<ref name=\"India's Vistara launches B737-800 ops\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/aviation/vistara-starts-phasing-out-9-boeing-737-planes/story/393665.html|title=Vistara to start phasing out it's 9 737-800|last=|first=|date=|website=ch-aviation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref>\n|12\n|&mdash; \n|156 \n|168\n|Former [[Jet Airways]] aircraft<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-vistara-aircraft-idINKCN1SU15R|title=Vistara leases six planes from BOC Aviation for local expansion|date=24 May 2019|via=in.reuters.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Boeing 787|Boeing 787-9]]\n|1\n|5<ref name=\"NewJets\">{{cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/vistara-orders-boeing-airbus/vistara-orders-boeing-airbus-jets-worth-31-billion-in-growth-plan-idINKBN1K10JL|title=Vistara orders Boeing, Airbus jets worth $3.1 billion in growth plan|accessdate=2018-07-12|date=2018-07-11|publisher=in.reuters.com|author=Aditi Shah, Jamie Freed}}</ref> \n|30\n|21\n|248\n|299\n|<ref> https://www.airvistara.com/trip/inflight-magazine/monthly/now </ref>\n|-\n! Total\n! 40\n! 52\n!colspan=\"6\" |\n|}\n</center>\n\nVistara took delivery of its first aircraft at New Delhi on 25 September 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-airbus-a-320-aircraft-in-delhi-114092500958_1.html|title=Vistara takes delivery of first Airbus A320 aircraft in Delhi|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=25 September 2014|access-date=25 September 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213022342/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-airbus-a-320-aircraft-in-delhi-114092500958_1.html|archivedate=13 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The airline took delivery of the last of its thirteen original Airbus A320 aircraft in October 2016<ref name=induction>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/business/aviation/vistara-airlines-completes-induction-of-airbus-a320-planes-3074848/ |title=Vistara airlines completes induction of Airbus A320 planes |agency=[[Press Trust of India]] |publisher=The Express Group |website=[[The Indian Express]] |date=10 October 2016 |access-date=10 October 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010204217/http://indianexpress.com/article/business/aviation/vistara-airlines-completes-induction-of-airbus-a320-planes-3074848/ |archivedate=10 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and plans to receive its seven Airbus A320neo aircraft by mid-2018.<ref name=induction/> In March 2015, Phee Teik Yeoh announced that the airline was planning to procure an unspecified number of both narrow-body and wide-body aircraft to enhance the domestic network and launch international flights within two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-plans-to-add-international-routes-expand-fleet/articleshow/46756305.cms|title=Vistara plans to add international routes, expand fleet|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=31 March 2015|access-date=31 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403052742/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-plans-to-add-international-routes-expand-fleet/articleshow/46756305.cms|archivedate=3 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/companies/20-aircraft-target-by-2018-is-just-the-tip-of-the-iceberg-phee-teik-yeoh-vistara-ceo/75021/|title=20-aircraft target by 2018 is just the tip of the iceberg: Phee Teik Yeoh, Vistara CEO|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|date=23 May 2015|access-date=24 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013000/http://www.financialexpress.com/article/companies/20-aircraft-target-by-2018-is-just-the-tip-of-the-iceberg-phee-teik-yeoh-vistara-ceo/75021/|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The airline recently inducted a number of former Jet Airways Boeing [[737-800|737-800NG]] to its fleet.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>Vistara is returning two of these nine leased Boeing 737 planes from January and the remaining seven will exit the fleet between 2022-23 as they are on long term.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vistara starts phasing out 9 Boeing 737 planes- Business News |url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/aviation/vistara-starts-phasing-out-9-boeing-737-planes/story/393665.html |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=www.businesstoday.in}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n===Cabin===\n====Business class====\nVistara offers 8 business class seats, two rows in 2-2 configuration, in its 158-seater Airbus A320-200 fleet. The business class seats are {{convert|20.12|in}} wide with {{convert|42|in}} [[seat pitch]].<ref name=\"Cabin re-config\">{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-reduces-seats-in-premium-class-cabins/articleshow/51189795.cms|title=Vistara reduces seats in premium class cabins|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=17 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024160435/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-reduces-seats-in-premium-class-cabins/articleshow/51189795.cms|archivedate=24 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Flight Review\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2015/03/inflight-review-vistara-business-class-airbus-a320-hyderabad-new-delhi.html|title=Inflight review: Vistara Business Class: Airbus A320: Hyderabad \u2013 New Delhi|work=Bangalore Aviation|date=25 March 2015|access-date=25 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327184400/http://www.bangaloreaviation.com/2015/03/inflight-review-vistara-business-class-airbus-a320-hyderabad-new-delhi.html|archivedate=27 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Premium Economy====\nVistara was the first airline in India to introduce Premium Economy class in the domestic market.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-takes-the-premium-economy-way-114122300979_1.html|title=Vistara takes the premium economy way|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=23 December 2014|access-date=2 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114164451/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-takes-the-premium-economy-way-114122300979_1.html|archivedate=14 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At present it offers 24 premium economy seats, four rows in 3-3 configuration, out of total 158 seats in the single aisle Airbus A320-200 aircraft in its fleet. Each being {{convert|18|in}} wide and having a pitch of {{convert|33-36|in}}.<ref name=\"Cabin re-config\"/>\n\n===In-flight entertainment===\nVistara World is the airline's wireless Wi-Fi inflight entertainment system that travellers can access on their personal handheld devices. Vistara selected a wireless IFE solution from Bluebox Aviation Systems to enable this service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blueboxaviation.com/bbwow-vistara/|title=Bluebox Wow to Fly Indian Skies with Vistara {{!}} Bluebox|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> It offers a multimedia library of over 70 hours\u2019 Bollywood and Hollywood content of various genres. It features movies of various categories such as Drama, Romance, Comedy, Thriller, Action, Adventure and Kids, as well as popular Indian and Western TV programmes and a selection of music including Indian, Pop, Jazz, Blues, Rock, Electronica and English Retro. Vistara World offers a live moving map display that allows one to track their aircraft as it flies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/|title=Business News, Shares Market, Stock Markets News LIVE \u2013 IPO, Mutual Funds, Income Tax and Finance News|website=Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref>\n\n===Catering===\nThe in-flight food is catered by [[SATS Ltd|TajSATS Air Catering]], another joint venture between Tata and a Singaporean company, headed by Chef Arun Batra, formerly the executive chef of the [[Taj Hotels Resorts and Palaces|Taj Hotels]] group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/food-in-high-places/article6827221.ece|title=Food in high places|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=27 January 2015|access-date=2 March 2015}}</ref> Vistara offers four different meals for each cabin for different time of the day \u2013 breakfast, refreshment, lunch and dinner with options of one vegetarian and one non-vegetarian dish in economy class; two vegetarian dishes and one non-vegetarian dish in premium economy; and two vegetarian and two non-vegetarian dishes for business-class cabin. The menu is typically changed every seventh day and there are different menus for lunch and dinner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://networkthoughts.in/vistaras-chefs-table-with-chef-arun-batra-giam-ming-toh-part-i/|title=Vistara\u2019s Chef\u2019s Table: With Chef Arun Batra & Giam Ming Toh|work=Network Thought|date=21 August 2015|access-date=17 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826021043/http://networkthoughts.in/vistaras-chefs-table-with-chef-arun-batra-giam-ming-toh-part-i/|archivedate=26 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also provides special meals upon request 24 hours before departure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/vistara-experience#inflight-dining-experience|title=Vistara:Inflight Dining|publisher=Vistara|access-date=22 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709090330/https://www.airvistara.com/trip/vistara-experience#inflight-dining-experience|archivedate=9 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/flying-and-feasting/article7569653.ece|title=Flying and feasting|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=22 August 2015|access-date=3 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194945/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/flying-and-feasting/article7569653.ece|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Lounge===\nOn 29 March 2016, Vistara inaugurated premium lounge service for its Business-class passengers and ''Club Vistara'' Platinum & Gold members at the departure level of Terminal 3 of Indira Gandhi International Airport at Delhi. The lounge was spread across 250 square metres on the air-side and could seat 75 people at a time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/vistara-unveils-signature-lounge-at-igi-airport-116032901204_1.html |title=Vistara unveils signature lounge at IGI airport |work=[[Business Standard]] |date=29 March 2016 |accessdate=29 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402053446/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/vistara-unveils-signature-lounge-at-igi-airport-116032901204_1.html |archivedate=2 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, on April 8th, Vistara sent an email to all its members confirming that they are closing down the lounge due to the expiry of their lease at the airport.\n\n==Frequent-flyer program==\nVistara uses ''Club Vistara'' as its [[frequent-flyer program]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/club-vistara|title=Club Vistara|publisher=Vistara|access-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/https://www.airvistara.com/trip/club-vistara|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> it operates as a value based program and awards points on the basis of money spent on tickets rather than miles travelled by passengers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/full-service-airlines-go-full-tilt-at-loyalty-programmes/50957/|title=Full-service airlines Vistara, Jet Airways, Air India go full tilt at loyalty programmes|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|date=7 March 2015|access-date=7 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309010016/http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/full-service-airlines-go-full-tilt-at-loyalty-programmes/50957/|archivedate=9 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 January 2015, Vistara announced a partnership agreement with [[Singapore Airlines]] which would allow Club Vistara members to earn and redeem miles with the [[KrisFlyer]] program on [[Singapore Airlines]] and [[SilkAir]] flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-vistara-launches-loyalty-scheme-with-singapor-airline-s-krisflyer-programme-2056571|title=Vistara launches loyalty scheme with Singapore Airline's KrisFlyer programme|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=29 January 2015|access-date=2 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402100233/http://www.dnaindia.com/money/report-vistara-launches-loyalty-scheme-with-singapor-airline-s-krisflyer-programme-2056571|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of airlines of India]]\n* [[List of airports in India]]\n* [[Transport in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Vistara}}\n* {{official website|http://www.airvistara.com}}\n\n{{airlines of India}}\n{{Tata Group}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Airlines of India]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Gurgaon]]\n[[Category:Tata Group]]\n[[Category:Singapore Airlines]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian airline}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2017}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline = Vistara\n| image = \n| logo = Vistara logo.svg\n| logo_size = 180\n| fleet_size = 40\n| destinations = 34\n| IATA = UK\n| ICAO = VTI\n| callsign = VISTARA\n| parent = \n<div>\n* [[Tata Sons]] (51%)\n* [[Singapore Airlines]] (49%)\n</div>\n| company_slogan = ''Fly the new feeling''\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2013}}\n| commenced = {{Start date|df=yes|2015|01|09}}\n| headquarters = Level 10, [[One Horizon Center]], Golf Course Rd, [[Gurgaon]]\n| key_people = {{ubl|Bhaskar Bhat ([[chairman]])|Leslie Thng ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| aoc = \n| hubs = {{nowrap|[[Indira Gandhi International Airport]]}}\n| secondary_hubs = \n| focus_cities = \n| frequent_flyer = Club Vistara\n| alliance = \n| num_employees = 900 (March 2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-way-to-fly|title=New way to fly: Vistara chief shakes up India's domestic travel|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=26 March 2016|access-date=26 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403095818/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-way-to-fly|archivedate=3 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.airvistara.com/|airvistara.com}}\n}}\n'''Tata SIA Airlines Limited''', operating as '''Vistara''', is an Indian  full-service [[airline]], based in [[Gurgaon]], with its hub at [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]]. The carrier, a joint venture between [[Tata Sons]] and [[Singapore Airlines]], commenced operations on 9 January 2015 with its inaugural flight between [[Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]]. The airline had carried more than two million passengers by June 2016<ref name=\"UK2million\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/vistara-looking-strategic-partnerships-expand-business-683235|title=Vistara looking at strategic partnerships to expand business|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=17 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618150139/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/vistara-looking-strategic-partnerships-expand-business-683235|archivedate=18 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and as of May 2019, has a 4.7% share <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/india-s-domestic-air-traffic-grows-3-in-may-after-registering-a-fall-in-april-1560858888397.html|title=India\u2019s domestic air traffic grows 3% in May after registering a fall in April|last=Kundu|first=Rhik|date=2019-06-18|website=Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-06-25}}</ref> of the domestic carrier market, making it the 6th largest domestic airline.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dgca.nic.in/reports/Traffic_reports/Traffic_Rep052017.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-07-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729172913/http://dgca.nic.in/reports/Traffic_reports/Traffic_Rep052017.pdf |archivedate=29 July 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The airline serves 34<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/destinations|title=Vistara/ Our Destinations|work=Vistara |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> destinations with a fleet of [[Airbus A320]], [[Boeing 787]] and [[Boeing 737 800|Boeing 737-800NG]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/airvistara/status/1134447502919372801|title=We are delighted to announce that our first commercial Boeing 737-800NG flight will fly this evening, Delhi-Amritsar-Delhi, UK695/694. Here's to loads more in the coming days and weeks! #FlyTheNewFeelingpic.twitter.com/G6qwSINFk9|last=Vistara|date=2019-05-31|website=@airvistara|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> aircraft.\n<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/auto/vistara-boeing-787-9-dreamliner-2541295.html</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Vistara Airbus A320-232 at Delhi Airport.jpg|thumb|right|Vistara's first Airbus A320 aircraft (VT-TTB)<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/31512-indias-vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft | title=India's Vistara takes delivery of first aircraft | work=[[ch-aviation]] | date=30 September 2014 | accessdate=30 July 2016 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817025842/http://ch-aviation.com/portal/news/31512-indias-vistara-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft | archivedate=17 August 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> at Delhi IGI Airport]]\n\nThe airline was founded in 2013 as a [[joint venture]] (JV) between India's conglomerate Tata Sons and Singapore Airlines (SIA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/VDL#al_profile_tab_info|title=Airline Information: Air Vistara (Ch-aviation)|publisher=[[Ch-aviation]]|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923185845/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/VDL#al_profile_tab_info|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"launch\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Tata-Sons-Singapore-Airlines-Vistara-set-for-October-launch/articleshow/40063616.cms|title=Tata Sons-Singapore Airlines 'Vistara' set for October launch|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=11 August 2014|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Tata-Sons-Singapore-Airlines-Vistara-set-for-October-launch/articleshow/40063616.cms|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-takes-to-the-skies-operates-first-flight-from-delhi-to-mumbai/articleshow/45823316.cms|title=Vistara takes to the skies, operates first flight from Delhi to Mumbai|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=9 January 2015|access-date=24 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827212527/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-takes-to-the-skies-operates-first-flight-from-delhi-to-mumbai/articleshow/45823316.cms|archivedate=27 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-carries-one-million-passengers/article8021439.ece|title=Vistara carries one million passengers|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=23 December 2015|access-date=23 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303131917/https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-carries-one-million-passengers/article8021439.ece|archivedate=3 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/press_release_news/ne130919.jsp|title=Tata, Singapore Airlines look to fly in Indian skies|work=[[Singapore Airlines]]|date=19 September 2013|access-date=12 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714171407/http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/press_release_news/ne130919.jsp|archivedate=14 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two companies had made a bid in the mid-1990s to launch a full service carrier in India that was unsuccessful, being denied regulatory approval by the Indian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/two-decades-in-the-departure-lounge-115010800788_1.html|title=Two decades in the departure lounge|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=9 January 2015|access-date=28 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035600/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/two-decades-in-the-departure-lounge-115010800788_1.html|archivedate=24 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With India opening up its airline sector for 49 percent [[foreign direct investment]] (FDI) in 2012, Tata and SIA once again decided to float a JV airline company in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/singapore-airlines-tata-joint-venture-proposal-would-be-a-big-boost-for-sia---and-airasia-129471|title=Singapore Airlines-Tata joint venture proposal would be a big boost for SIA \u2013 and AirAsia?|publisher=CAPA|date=20 September 2013|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/singapore-airlines-tata-joint-venture-proposal-would-be-a-big-boost-for-sia---and-airasia-129471|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The JV, Tata SIA Airlines Limited (TSAL), was envisaged as a premium full-service carrier to cater to the demands of [[high-end]] business travellers in India's civil aviation market dominated by [[low-cost carrier]]s. India's [[Foreign Investment Promotion Board]] approved the JV in October 2013, allowing SIA to take a 49 percent stake in the airline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-tata-proposal-gets-green-light-indias-foreign-investment-board-201|title=SIA, Tata proposal gets green light from India's foreign investment board|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=24 October 2013|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022135529/http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-tata-proposal-gets-green-light-indias-foreign-investment-board-201|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two parent companies initially pledged to invest a combined {{US$|100mn|link=yes}} as start-up capital, with Tata Sons owning 51 percent and Singapore Airlines owning the remaining 49 percent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-partners-tata-group-set-new-airline-india-20130919|title=SIA partners Tata group to set up new airline in India|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|date=19 September 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022134011/http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/sia-partners-tata-group-set-new-airline-india-20130919|archivedate=22 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was part of Tata's second major foray into the aviation sector along with a minority stake in [[AirAsia India]].<ref name=\"reborn\">{{cite news|title=With Vistara, a Tata airline is reborn|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/with-vistara-a-tata-airline-is-reborn-115010800126_1.html|first=Aneesh|last=Phadnis|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|location=Mumbai|date=9 January 2015|access-date=13 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607131134/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/with-vistara-a-tata-airline-is-reborn-115010800126_1.html|archivedate=7 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The company's first venture, Tata Airlines, was established in the 1930s and later became the flag carrier [[Air India]] after nationalization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/todays-newspaper/tata-forays-into-sky-with-vistara.html|title=Tata forays into the skies with Vistara|newspaper=[[The Pioneer (newspaper)|The Pioneer]]|date=12 August 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923232359/http://www.dailypioneer.com/todays-newspaper/tata-forays-into-sky-with-vistara.html|archivedate=23 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe company unveiled its brand identity \"Vistara\" on 11 August 2014.<ref name=\"launch\"/> The name was taken from the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vist\u0101ra'', meaning \"limitless expanse\".<ref name=\"vistara\">{{cite press release|title=Tata SIA christens its airline, Vistara|url=http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/Tata-SIA-christens-its-airline-Vistara|work=[[Tata Sons]]|date=14 August 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113222042/http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/Tata-SIA-christens-its-airline-Vistara|archivedate=13 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"vistarameaning\">{{cite web|title=Vistara meaning|url=http://www.spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=HK&beginning=0+&tinput=+vistara&trans=Translate&direction=AU|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224063529/http://www.spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=HK&beginning=0+&tinput=+vistara&trans=Translate&direction=AU|archivedate=24 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara received its [[air operator's certificate]] from the [[Directorate General of Civil Aviation (India)|Directorate General of Civil Aviation]] on 15 December 2014 and started operations on 9 January 2015.<ref name=\"reborn\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-set-to-take-off-in-jan-gets-air-operator-permit-114121500939_1.html|title=Vistara gets air operator permit, to take off in Jan|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=16 December 2014|access-date=4 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216131327/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/vistara-set-to-take-off-in-jan-gets-air-operator-permit-114121500939_1.html|archivedate=16 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-12-15/news/57072156_1_vistara-phee-teik-yeoh-full-service-airline|title=Tata-Singapore Airlines joint venture airline Vistara gets flying permit, to announce schedule soon|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=15 December 2014|access-date=8 December 2015}}</ref> Vistara became the first carrier to operate domestic services out of the new Terminal 2 at Mumbai's [[Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-operate-out-of-mumbai-international-airports-new-t2-terminal/articleshow/45712273.cms|title=Vistara to operate out of Mumbai International Airport\u2019s new T2 terminal|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=1 January 2015|access-date=2 January 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827224102/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-operate-out-of-mumbai-international-airports-new-t2-terminal/articleshow/45712273.cms|archivedate=27 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 24 August 2015, Vistara inaugurated the Aviation Security Training Institute, an in-house institute for training its cockpit and cabin crew, security staff and others related to aviation industry. The institute has secured the necessary approvals from the nodal body [[Bureau of Civil Aviation Security]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-08-24/news/65808454_1_vistara-joint-venture-carrier-aviation-security-training-institute|title=Tata-SIA joint venture carrier Vistara sets up security training institute|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=24 August 2015|access-date=30 August 2015}}</ref> From the first month of operation, Vistara consistently achieved very high [[on-time performance]] records of over 90 percent, the highest among India's domestic carriers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/money/interview-we-are-still-a-crawling-infant-wait-for-us-to-get-up-and-run-says-vistara-2116201|title=We are still a crawling infant, wait for us to get up and run, says Vistara|newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|date=20 August 2015|access-date=20 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820213044/http://www.dnaindia.com/money/interview-we-are-still-a-crawling-infant-wait-for-us-to-get-up-and-run-says-vistara-2116201|archivedate=20 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistaras-otp-stands-at-89-per-cent-in-1st-month-of-operation/article6933544.ece|title=Vistara\u2019s OTP stands at 89 percent in 1st month of operation|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=25 February 2015|access-date=2 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194945/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistaras-otp-stands-at-89-per-cent-in-1st-month-of-operation/article6933544.ece|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 20 August 2015, Vistara declared it had carried half a million passengers in just over seven months of operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://centreforaviation.com/news/vistara-reaches-500000-pax-milestone-475569|title=Vistara reaches 500,000 pax milestone|work=CAPA|date=21 August 2015|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194944/http://centreforaviation.com/news/vistara-reaches-500000-pax-milestone-475569|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of February 2016, Vistara has a share of 2% in the domestic carrier market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-domestic-passenger-demand-up-25-percent-iata-116040700595_1.html|title=India's domestic passenger demand up 25 percent: IATA|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=6 April 2014|access-date=14 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423143800/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-domestic-passenger-demand-up-25-percent-iata-116040700595_1.html|archivedate=23 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara recently received the membership of the International Air Transport Association (IATA),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/vistara-joins-global-airlines-body-iata-ahead-of-international-operations/article23710253.ece|title=Vistara joins global airlines\u2019 body IATA ahead of international operations|work=@businessline|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref> joining the association of more than 280 airlines around the world that represents, leads and serves the airline industry. With this, Vistara becomes one of the select few airlines in India to have the IATA membership.\n\nVistara announced on 11 July 2019 that their first international destination would be Singapore. The airline started its first international service from Delhi to Singapore and Mumbai to Singapore on 6 and 7 August respectively using the [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800 NG]] which was earlier used by [[Jet Airways]].<ref>{{cite news |title=India's Vistara to launch international flights, starting with Singapore in August |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/vistara-new-singapore-india-flight-date-delhi-mumbai-11711134 |accessdate=11 July 2019 |work=CNA |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chowdhury |first1=Anirban |title=Vistara to launch international operations to Singapore from August |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/vistara-to-launch-international-operations-to-singapore-from-august/articleshow/70163712.cms |accessdate=11 July 2019 |work=The Economic Times |date=10 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/vistara-makes-international-debut-on-an-aircraft-used-by-jet-airways-4300881.html|title=Vistara makes international debut, on an aircraft used by Jet Airways|work=Moneycontrol.com|date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February 2020, the airline took the delivery of its first wide-body [[Boeing 787-9]], becoming the first Indian airline to operate this aircraft and yet to receive five more such aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vistara takes delivery of India's first Dreamliner plane with lie-flat business class seats |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/vistara-delivery-india-first-dreamliner-plane-lie-flat-business-class-seats-1650728-2020-02-28 |accessdate=5 March 2020 |work=India Today |agency=Press Trust of India |date=28 February 2020 |location=Washington |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate affairs==\nOn 15 April 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://site2corp.com/in/phee-teik-yeoh-2/companies|title=Phee Teik Yeoh \u2013 Director / Owner Information|website=site2corp.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001162751/http://site2corp.com/in/phee-teik-yeoh-2/companies|archivedate=1 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vistara chose Mr Phee Teik Yeoh as the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) and Mr Giam Ming Toh<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketnewsalert.com/2015/04/Mr-Giam-Ming-Toh-is-the-Chief-Commercial-Officer-of-Vistara.html|title=Mr Giam Ming Toh is the Chief Commercial Officer of Vistara|website=www.pocketnewsalert.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001165816/http://www.pocketnewsalert.com/2015/04/Mr-Giam-Ming-Toh-is-the-Chief-Commercial-Officer-of-Vistara.html|archivedate=1 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as the [[chief commercial officer]] (CCO), both from Singapore Airlines.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/ready-to-fly-vistara-poaches-key-men-from-indigo-jetlite/article1-1261191.aspx|title=Vistara poaches key men from IndiGo, JetLite|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=8 September 2014|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104203613/http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/ready-to-fly-vistara-poaches-key-men-from-indigo-jetlite/article1-1261191.aspx|archivedate=4 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Vistara shifted to its new office at the [[One Horizon Center]] tower in Sector 43, [[Gurgaon]], a [[satellite city]] of Delhi.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/few-takers-for-office-space-in-metro-cities/46642/|title=Few takers for office space in metro cities|newspaper=[[The Financial Express (India)|Financial Express]]|date=24 February 2015|access-date=8 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415065335/http://www.financialexpress.com/article/industry/companies/few-takers-for-office-space-in-metro-cities/46642/|archivedate=15 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/vistara-chases-small-aviation-market-with-big-ambitions/1/217140.html|title=Battle of Class|newspaper=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]]|date=April 2015|access-date=8 April 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403180651/http://businesstoday.intoday.in/story/vistara-chases-small-aviation-market-with-big-ambitions/1/217140.html|archivedate=3 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Initially it started out with a three-member board comprising Swee Wah Mak (SIA group), Mukund Rajan and Prasad Menon (Tata group), with the latter as chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistara-spreads-wings-to-add-goa-hyderabad-flights-by-march/article6815635.ece|title=Vistara spreads wings; to add Goa, Hyderabad flights by March|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=23 January 2015|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110194945/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/vistara-spreads-wings-to-add-goa-hyderabad-flights-by-march/article6815635.ece|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/people-first-vistaras-top-executives-spending-time-with-employees-on-the-ground-tackling-issues/articleshow/48565166.cms|title='People first': Vistara's top executives spending time with employees on the ground & tackling issues|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=21 August 2015|access-date=21 August 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150825050954/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/people-first-vistaras-top-executives-spending-time-with-employees-on-the-ground-tackling-issues/articleshow/48565166.cms|archivedate=25 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In August 2015, the airline expanded the board by introducing two new members, Som Mittal and Sangeeta Pendurkar, along with an equity infusion of {{INRconvert|2|b}}, part of {{INRconvert|5|b}} initially planned by Tata and SIA together.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/tata-sia-infuse-rs-500-crore-in-vistara-115090600209_1.html|title=Tata Sons, SIA infuse Rs 500 cr in Vistara|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=6 September 2015|access-date=6 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907210800/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/tata-sia-infuse-rs-500-crore-in-vistara-115090600209_1.html|archivedate=7 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/40091-tata-group-singapore-airlines-boost-vistaras-coffers|title=Tata Group, Singapore Airlines boost Vistara's coffers|work=[[Ch-aviation]]|date=8 September 2015|access-date=9 September 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910151101/http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/40091-tata-group-singapore-airlines-boost-vistaras-coffers|archivedate=10 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2016, Bhaskar Bhat, present Managing Director of [[Titan Company|Titan]], joined as the new chairman following Prasad Menon's retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.titan.co.in/control//Corporate/Board-of-Directors|title=Titan Company Board of Directors|work=[[Titan Company|Titan]]|date=18 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117110607/http://www.titan.co.in/control/Corporate/Board-of-Directors|archivedate=17 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/ZRdG7GYaYyW1cSd0uYRvjO/Bhaskar-Bhat-named-Vistara-chairman.html|title=Bhaskar Bhat named Vistara chairman|newspaper=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|date=14 January 2016|access-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117191207/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/ZRdG7GYaYyW1cSd0uYRvjO/Bhaskar-Bhat-named-Vistara-chairman.html|archivedate=17 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bhaskar-bhat-joins-vistara-as-chairman-116011400857_1.html|title=Bhaskar Bhat joins Vistara as chairman|newspaper=[[Business Standard]]|date=14 January 2016|access-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302140304/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/bhaskar-bhat-joins-vistara-as-chairman-116011400857_1.html|archivedate=2 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In March 2016, Vistara appointed Sanjiv Kapoor as its chief strategy and commercial officer as the successor to Giam Ming Toh who was scheduled to leave in mid April 2016 following completion of his deputation at Vistara.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/former-spicejet-coo-sanjiv-kapoor-joins-vistara-as-commercial-and-strategy-chief/articleshow/51205907.cms|title=Former SpiceJet COO Sanjiv Kapoor joins Vistara as commercial and strategy chief|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=28 March 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403002936/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/former-spicejet-coo-sanjiv-kapoor-joins-vistara-as-commercial-and-strategy-chief/articleshow/51205907.cms|archivedate=3 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 October 2017, it was announced that Leslie Thng would succeed Yeoh Phee Teik as CEO of Vistara.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/leslie-thng-vistara-chief-executive-officer|title=Leslie Thng joins Vistara as chief executive officer via @tatacompanies|work=tata.com|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201193009/http://www.tata.com/company/releasesinside/leslie-thng-vistara-chief-executive-officer|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mr Yeoh returned to Singapore  Airlines to take up a senior management role as Acting Senior Vice President of Customer Experience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/vistara-ceo-phee-teik-yeoh-likely-to-join-sia/articleshow/61060156.cms|title=Vistara CEO Phee Teik Yeoh likely to join SIA as product & customer service head|last=Mishra|first=Mihir|date=2017-10-13|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-02-01|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201192954/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/vistara-ceo-phee-teik-yeoh-likely-to-join-sia/articleshow/61060156.cms|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mr Thng was serving as Chief Commercial Officer of Budget Aviation Holdings, a Singapore Airlines subsidiary, prior to his appointment in Vistara.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/top-level-shuffles-in-the-sia-group/|title=Top level shuffle in the SIA group|last=Manjur|first=Rezwana|work=Marketing Interactive|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201193005/http://www.marketing-interactive.com/top-level-shuffles-in-the-sia-group/|archivedate=1 February 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Before that, Mr Thng was the Chief Executive Officer of SilkAir, a full service regional airline under Singapore Airlines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://centreforaviation.com/news/silkair-names-new-ceo-168199|title=SilkAir names new CEO |website=centreforaviation.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\n{{Main|List of Vistara destinations}}\nAs of October 2019, Vistara serves 24 destinations with over 1200 flights a week.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airvistara.com/trip/company-info|title=About Vistara \u2013 Tata Singapore Airlines Joint Venture|website=www.airvistara.com}}</ref>   Its only hub is at the [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]] from where it operates all of its flights. Vistara's first flight was on 9 January 2015, from Delhi to Mumbai.<ref name=\"auto\"/> On 6 August 2019, the airline launched its first international flight from Delhi to Singapore using a [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800NG]] aircraft which was earlier used by [[Jet Airways]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/companies/vistara-makes-international-debut-on-an-aircraft-used-by-jet-airways-4300881.html|title=Vistara makes international debut, on an aircraft used by Jet Airways|work=Moneycontrol.com|date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Codeshare agreements===\nVistara [[codeshare agreement|codeshares]] with the following airlines:\n*[[British Airways]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massy-Beresford |first1=Helen |title=British Airways to codeshare with Indian domestic carrier Vistara |url=http://atwonline.com/airlines/british-airways-codeshare-indian-domestic-carrier-vistara |publisher=[[Air Transport World]] |date=6 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914161536/http://atwonline.com/airlines/british-airways-codeshare-indian-domestic-carrier-vistara |archivedate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n* [[SilkAir]]<ref name=\"Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.singaporeair.com/en_UK/us/media-centre/press-release/article/?q=en_UK/2017/January-March/jr0617-170314|title=Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights|website=www.singaporeair.com}}</ref>\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]<ref name=\"Singapore Airlines And SilkAir To Codeshare On Vistara Flights\" />\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[United Airlines]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.united.com/2019-06-18-united-airlines-and-vistara-establish-codeshare-agreement-2638904487.html|title=United Airlines and Vistara Establish Codeshare Agreement|date=2019-06-18|website=United Hub|language=en|access-date=2019-06-22}}</ref>\n* [[Deutsche Lufthansa|Lufthansa]]<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/vistara-signs-codeshare-agreement-with-lufthansa/articleshow/72438123.cms</ref>\n\n===Interline agreements===\nVistara has [[interline agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=VistaraInterline>{{cite web|url=https://airvistara.com/trip/interline-partners|title=Vistara Interline Patners|publisher=Vistara|accessdate=6 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103193600/https://airvistara.com/trip/interline-partners |archive-date=2016-11-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Aeroflot]]\n* [[Air France]]\n* [[Air Mauritius]] \n* [[All Nippon Airways]]\n* [[Asiana Airlines]]\n* [[British Airways]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/british-airways-may-expand-its-interline-agreement-with-vistara/articleshow/49541297.cms|title=British Airways may expand its interline agreement with Vistara \u2013 The Economic Times|website=The Economic Times|access-date=2016-06-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921170150/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/british-airways-may-expand-its-interline-agreement-with-vistara/articleshow/49541297.cms|archivedate=21 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] \n* [[Ethiopian Airlines]]\n* [[Finnair]]\n* [[flydubai]]\n* [[Gulf Air]]\n* [[Japan Airlines]]\n* [[Kenya Airways]]\n* [[KLM]]\n* [[Kuwait Airways]]\n* [[Qatar Airways]]<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2017/Aug/qatar-airways_-new-interline-partnership-takes-off-with-vistara.html# |title=Qatar Airways\u2019 New Interline Partnership Takes Off With Vistara |publisher=Qatar Airways |date=22 August 2017 |access-date=25 August 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825111835/https://www.qatarairways.com/en/press-releases/2017/Aug/qatar-airways_-new-interline-partnership-takes-off-with-vistara.html|archivedate=25 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[SilkAir]]\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]<ref name=codeshare>{{cite news|first=P.R.|last=Sanjai|title=Vistara signs inter-line agreement with Singapore Airlines, SilkAir|url=http://www.livemint.com/Companies/VrpAhLBg97M3RffJN9pm2M/Vistara-signs-interline-agreement-with-Singapore-Air-Silk.html|newspaper=[[Live Mint]]|access-date=2 January 2015|date=22 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102131039/http://www.livemint.com/Companies/VrpAhLBg97M3RffJN9pm2M/Vistara-signs-interline-agreement-with-Singapore-Air-Silk.html|archivedate=2 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Sri Lankan Airlines]]\n* [[Turkish Airlines]]\n* [[United Airlines]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Fleet==\n[[File:Vistara_VT-TTF_at_Bengaluru,_2016-02-20.jpg|thumb|Vistara [[Airbus A320-200]]]]\n[[File:Vistara VT-TSD Dreamliner.jpg|thumb|VT-TSD, the first [[Boeing 787-9]] in the airline's fleet.]]\n{{As of|2019|12}}, the Vistara fleet consists of the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite journal |title=Global Airline Guide 2019 (Part One) |journal=Airliner World |issue=October 2019 |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dron|first1=Alan|title=India\u2019s Vistara prepares for international services|url=http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/india-s-vistara-prepares-international-services|publisher=[[Air Transport World]]|date=6 April 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418080754/http://atwonline.com/airports-routes/india-s-vistara-prepares-international-services|archivedate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Airbus_Orders\">{{cite web|url= https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o&d/ODs-November-2019-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft.xlsx|title= Airbus orders and deliveries|publisher= Airbus|date= November 2019|archive-date= 7 December 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191207004822/https://www.airbus.com/content/dam/corporate-topics/publications/o&d/ODs-November-2019-Airbus-Commercial-Aircraft.xlsx|access-date= 7 December 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Vistara fleet\n|- \n|- style=\"background:#662046;\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" styl